1
00:00:31,834 --> 00:00:33,834
[Last winter,]

2
00:00:33,834 --> 00:00:35,869
[we threw down a challenge]

3
00:00:35,869 --> 00:00:39,867
[to Korea's top chefs]

4
00:00:39,867 --> 00:00:42,034
[Three chefs stepped up]

5
00:00:42,034 --> 00:00:43,467
Think we can pull this off.

6
00:00:43,467 --> 00:00:45,267
[and took it on]
Honestly, five days feels like overkill.

7
00:00:45,267 --> 00:00:47,047
Three days should do it, right?

8
00:00:47,047 --> 00:00:49,248
Doesn't bother me one bit.
Sleep is optional, really.

9
00:00:49,248 --> 00:00:51,237
This sounds like a blast.

10
00:00:53,340 --> 00:00:56,009
[Drop the titles]

11
00:00:56,009 --> 00:00:58,090
[start as a kitchen rookie abroad]

12
00:00:58,090 --> 00:00:59,679
[No name, no resume, strange kitchen]
Reading the room matters a ton.

13
00:00:59,679 --> 00:01:00,614
Hello.

14
00:01:00,614 --> 00:01:03,049
- Kwon! Get over here.
- Okay.

15
00:01:03,049 --> 00:01:04,668
[Slammed, totally slammed]

16
00:01:04,668 --> 00:01:06,431
[Let the skills do the talking]
I was pretty much ready for it.

17
00:01:06,431 --> 00:01:09,701
Breaking some stereotypes would be nice.

18
00:01:09,701 --> 00:01:11,995
[Only five days on the clock]

19
00:01:11,995 --> 00:01:14,394
It threw me off a little, honestly.

20
00:01:14,394 --> 00:01:15,367
Why am I even here?

21
00:01:15,367 --> 00:01:17,701
[Stay stuck at the bottom rung]
Total head spin.

22
00:01:17,701 --> 00:01:18,798
Gosh.

23
00:01:18,798 --> 00:01:21,201
I'm sorry.

24
00:01:21,201 --> 00:01:24,150
[or grab the shot at something more]
"She doesn't even cook, what does she know?"

25
00:01:24,150 --> 00:01:26,105
Tastes super burnt, huh?

26
00:01:28,267 --> 00:01:30,001
Keep doing that.

27
00:01:30,001 --> 00:01:32,300
You'll lose your spot.

28
00:01:32,300 --> 00:01:33,647
[Tossing it?]
I'm so sorry.

29
00:01:33,647 --> 00:01:35,582
No problem.

30
00:01:35,582 --> 00:01:37,201
I mapped it out first.

31
00:01:37,201 --> 00:01:39,720
If it's okay with you...

32
00:01:39,720 --> 00:01:41,334
Mind if I take a shot at cooking?

33
00:01:41,334 --> 00:01:43,627
- Of course.
- Really?

34
00:01:43,627 --> 00:01:46,259
I figured I should just cook my own dish.

35
00:01:46,259 --> 00:01:47,328
[No time to sit around waiting]

36
00:01:47,328 --> 00:01:49,467
I held back so much, seriously.

37
00:01:49,467 --> 00:01:51,035
[Win over the locals' palate]

38
00:01:51,035 --> 00:01:52,601
[and in just five days]

39
00:01:53,801 --> 00:01:56,255
[climb up to head chef]

40
00:01:56,255 --> 00:01:57,508
I really need to bring my A game.

41
00:01:57,508 --> 00:01:59,218
[At the end of it all]

42
00:01:59,218 --> 00:02:00,390
[getting a new dish on this menu]
Okay, this is really

43
00:02:00,390 --> 00:02:01,873
[is the whole endgame]
happening now.

44
00:02:01,873 --> 00:02:03,615
[Identities under wraps]
My drive felt totally different.

45
00:02:03,615 --> 00:02:05,350
[The only weapon is raw skill]
It's a battle of pride.

46
00:02:05,350 --> 00:02:06,579
I've got nothing to lose either.

47
00:02:06,579 --> 00:02:07,885
So I might as well swing for it.

48
00:02:07,885 --> 00:02:11,272
[Strip the titles, back to the roots]
[Undercover Chef]

49
00:02:11,272 --> 00:02:14,418
Top chef in Korea, right? Our Sam Kim.

50
00:02:14,418 --> 00:02:16,278
Jung Ji Sun.

51
00:02:16,278 --> 00:02:18,706
And Kwon Sung Jun.

52
00:02:18,706 --> 00:02:19,939
The three of you here.

53
00:02:19,939 --> 00:02:21,499
You guys mad at me?

54
00:02:22,506 --> 00:02:24,138
So...

55
00:02:24,138 --> 00:02:25,509
- No, I mean...
- It was so rough...

56
00:02:25,509 --> 00:02:26,772
- Oh, it was rough?
- Rough. So rough.

57
00:02:26,772 --> 00:02:28,072
- Still feeling it now?
- So rough.

58
00:02:28,072 --> 00:02:29,205
[Rookie days still hitting hard?]
I still haven't bounced back.

59
00:02:29,205 --> 00:02:32,472
Honestly, this kid asking us feels weird.

60
00:02:32,472 --> 00:02:33,806
[Writer Kim Pung, solo MC of Undercover Chef]
Why is that?

61
00:02:33,806 --> 00:02:37,390
Not sure he'll really get
where we're coming from.

62
00:02:37,390 --> 00:02:39,651
If I got it that well, I'd be the chef myself.

63
00:02:39,651 --> 00:02:41,372
- Right.
- Yeah.

64
00:02:41,372 --> 00:02:43,621
- But the thing is, all of this in five days!
- Yeah.

65
00:02:43,621 --> 00:02:46,758
[Sneak into a foreign kitchen as a rookie]
Starting from the bottom prepping ingredients,

66
00:02:46,758 --> 00:02:49,087
[Five days to land a new dish on the menu]
ending with putting your own dish out.

67
00:02:49,087 --> 00:02:51,567
- Yeah, exactly.
- You're getting your own dish on the menu.

68
00:02:51,567 --> 00:02:53,339
- Yeah, that's right.
- But honestly,

69
00:02:53,339 --> 00:02:55,587
is five days even doable?

70
00:02:55,587 --> 00:02:57,835
You know what I said

71
00:02:57,835 --> 00:03:00,247
- the first time I heard this?
- What did you say?

72
00:03:00,247 --> 00:03:02,746
You guys really don't know
anything about cooking.

73
00:03:02,746 --> 00:03:04,247
That's what I told the producers.

74
00:03:04,247 --> 00:03:07,005
- Honestly, when I first heard this too,
- Right?

75
00:03:07,005 --> 00:03:11,158
- they're way underestimating this field.
- Total disrespect.

76
00:03:11,158 --> 00:03:12,718
- That's what I thought.
- I mean, seriously,

77
00:03:12,718 --> 00:03:14,719
[Even an outsider sees it's impossible]
- makes zero sense. - Zero sense.

78
00:03:14,719 --> 00:03:17,606
- Figured there'd be some setup behind it.
- Right.

79
00:03:17,606 --> 00:03:19,058
- That's what I was thinking.
- Yeah.

80
00:03:19,058 --> 00:03:22,839
- Heard they basically just dropped you off
- Right.

81
00:03:22,839 --> 00:03:24,047
- and bailed.
- Just left me there.

82
00:03:24,047 --> 00:03:26,731
- Wait, am I even allowed to say this?
- Yeah.

83
00:03:26,731 --> 00:03:28,806
- So I asked the writers,
- Yeah.

84
00:03:28,806 --> 00:03:31,101
why come to Italy with me at all?

85
00:03:32,047 --> 00:03:34,488
- They didn't tell me a single thing.
- Right, dumped you there.

86
00:03:34,488 --> 00:03:36,708
- And said sort it out.
- And then they just slipped off.

87
00:03:36,708 --> 00:03:39,210
Why not just watch the tape back home?

88
00:03:39,210 --> 00:03:41,612
- From the jump...
- Please give us a script.

89
00:03:41,612 --> 00:03:44,115
[Five days as the lowest rookie, no exit]
Give me something, anything.

90
00:03:44,115 --> 00:03:46,706
- What's the move? Please.
- For me, when I ran into them coming in,

91
00:03:46,706 --> 00:03:48,205
"hi there."

92
00:03:48,205 --> 00:03:49,847
[That wraps up the day with the crew]
- And clocking out. - Right.

93
00:03:49,847 --> 00:03:51,448
- That's the whole thing.
- Seriously?

94
00:03:51,448 --> 00:03:53,825
- That's how it went?
- That's the whole thing.

95
00:03:53,825 --> 00:03:55,606
[Real life, no filter whatsoever]
This is the real deal, honestly.

96
00:03:55,606 --> 00:03:56,728
It got way too real.

97
00:03:56,728 --> 00:03:58,529
There's something I've been wondering.

98
00:03:58,529 --> 00:04:00,164
[Q. About the restaurants you snuck into,]
With this many cameras around...

99
00:04:00,164 --> 00:04:01,706
[how did they know the three of you at first?]
How do you even pull that off?

100
00:04:01,706 --> 00:04:04,806
- Right.
- So even the owner had no clue?

101
00:04:04,806 --> 00:04:06,404
My guess is he had zero idea.

102
00:04:06,404 --> 00:04:08,138
- Yeah, exactly.
- He totally had no clue.

103
00:04:08,138 --> 00:04:09,244
- For real, not a clue.
- Seriously.

104
00:04:09,244 --> 00:04:11,942
Honestly, I wondered
if we needed to hide it this much.

105
00:04:13,144 --> 00:04:15,680
[One month before going undercover,]

106
00:04:17,815 --> 00:04:22,820
[The restaurants set for the chefs'
infiltration were told the following story]

107
00:04:22,820 --> 00:04:24,188
[Not as star chefs, but...]

108
00:04:24,188 --> 00:04:26,991
[Retired celebrities from their main fields]

109
00:04:26,991 --> 00:04:28,392
[Not for a variety show, but...]

110
00:04:28,392 --> 00:04:31,562
[shooting a documentary]

111
00:04:31,562 --> 00:04:33,865
[To open their own restaurant,]

112
00:04:33,865 --> 00:04:37,535
[for five days, starting from the bottom rung
and putting in real work, that was the cover]

113
00:04:37,535 --> 00:04:39,242
[Keeping that cover intact]

114
00:04:39,242 --> 00:04:43,274
I'm dying to hear how each of you
handled life as a rookie.

115
00:04:43,274 --> 00:04:46,778
[The undercover chefs' secret work diary!]
- First undercover chef. - Finally.

116
00:04:46,778 --> 00:04:48,615
- It'd be fun.
- He's going back 27 years.

117
00:04:48,615 --> 00:04:53,151
- Whoa, 27 years.
- Back to rookie after 27 years.

118
00:04:53,151 --> 00:04:55,372
[What's Sam Kim like now?]
Starting with Chef Sam Kim's clip.

119
00:04:55,372 --> 00:04:57,172
- Oh, why me first?
- Let's take a look.

120
00:04:57,172 --> 00:05:00,424
So lucky. He's first. I wanted to go first.

121
00:05:03,194 --> 00:05:07,565
[First Undercover Chef]

122
00:05:07,565 --> 00:05:09,233
[The legend who launched Korea's chef era]

123
00:05:09,233 --> 00:05:11,172
Oh, that's cool.

124
00:05:11,172 --> 00:05:12,103
Hi,

125
00:05:12,103 --> 00:05:15,807
[Korea's top Italian chef]
I'm Sam Kim. I cook Italian.

126
00:05:15,807 --> 00:05:20,244
I run two restaurants as the owner-chef.

127
00:05:20,244 --> 00:05:22,589
We have 26 staff.

128
00:05:22,589 --> 00:05:25,650
I juggle management and more.

129
00:05:25,650 --> 00:05:27,685
[When you think of pasta in Korea]

130
00:05:27,685 --> 00:05:30,288
[He's the first name that comes up]

131
00:05:30,288 --> 00:05:34,826
[The maestro who made pasta mainstream]

132
00:05:34,826 --> 00:05:38,596
I started cooking at 23,
so that makes it 27 years for me.

133
00:05:38,596 --> 00:05:40,498
[A seasoned chef of 27 years]

134
00:05:40,498 --> 00:05:43,334
[27 years staying true
A master of Italian cuisine]

135
00:05:43,334 --> 00:05:46,938
[First-gen star chef Sam Kim]

136
00:05:46,938 --> 00:05:48,840
[Chef Sam Kim, what kind of rookie were you?]

137
00:05:48,840 --> 00:05:49,757
Me?

138
00:05:49,757 --> 00:05:51,305
Oh, well, I...

139
00:05:51,305 --> 00:05:54,946
[Whoosh] [Staff]
I tell my staff this with pride.

140
00:05:54,946 --> 00:05:58,672
The bosses adored me as a rookie.

141
00:05:58,672 --> 00:06:00,851
- Oh, I bet. I bet they did.
- With pride?

142
00:06:00,851 --> 00:06:02,086
[Staff all stunned]
I mean, yeah.

143
00:06:02,086 --> 00:06:03,888
Yeah, I really worked hard.

144
00:06:03,888 --> 00:06:06,339
[Snicker]
So a lot of them liked me.

145
00:06:06,339 --> 00:06:09,127
[Sam Kim's back-in-my-day...]
Back in my day.

146
00:06:09,127 --> 00:06:11,095
[Flying around!]
My legs were a total blur.

147
00:06:12,123 --> 00:06:14,418
[Sam Kim 17 years ago]
I could juggle tons of tasks.

148
00:06:14,418 --> 00:06:15,872
Stuff like that.

149
00:06:17,255 --> 00:06:18,619
You look better now, honestly.

150
00:06:18,619 --> 00:06:20,583
[Why did he fly around
till he was skin and bones?]

151
00:06:20,583 --> 00:06:22,907
I started out working overseas.

152
00:06:22,907 --> 00:06:25,784
I had to survive, so I pushed harder.

153
00:06:25,784 --> 00:06:28,138
Being Asian,

154
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:29,739
my coworkers assumed...

155
00:06:29,739 --> 00:06:32,884
[He can't cook Western food!]
"This guy probably can't cook well."

156
00:06:32,884 --> 00:06:36,153
I worked twice

157
00:06:36,153 --> 00:06:39,090
as hard to get noticed.

158
00:06:39,090 --> 00:06:42,526
Needed to stand out somehow.

159
00:06:42,526 --> 00:06:43,772
[So what did you do?]

160
00:06:43,772 --> 00:06:45,498
Back then, you mean?

161
00:06:45,498 --> 00:06:49,033
I'd show up before the senior chefs got in,

162
00:06:49,033 --> 00:06:50,768
and snap some pictures,

163
00:06:50,768 --> 00:06:53,339
then even if it wasn't perfect,

164
00:06:53,339 --> 00:06:55,439
if a few things were set up,
the seniors would see it.

165
00:06:55,439 --> 00:06:56,819
Huh? Check this kid out.

166
00:06:56,819 --> 00:06:58,838
They'd be pleased like that.

167
00:06:58,838 --> 00:07:00,979
Like, oh, the kid's really putting in effort.

168
00:07:00,979 --> 00:07:02,719
[Pretty good, right? Hehe]
When you hustle like that,

169
00:07:02,719 --> 00:07:04,957
- they can't help but warm up to you.
- Right.

170
00:07:04,957 --> 00:07:08,519
It backfired on me a couple of times though.

171
00:07:08,519 --> 00:07:10,621
I got chewed out, like,
"Who told you to do that?"

172
00:07:10,621 --> 00:07:14,158
[Smart rookie hack snap photos to remember!]
But overall, they took it well.

173
00:07:15,158 --> 00:07:17,228
Then once the seniors showed up,

174
00:07:17,228 --> 00:07:19,506
I'd make a cup of coffee for each of them.

175
00:07:19,506 --> 00:07:21,839
That's right.

176
00:07:21,839 --> 00:07:26,046
Back in the day,
I wasn't really into Americano.

177
00:07:26,046 --> 00:07:27,886
[Rookie days abroad Americano hater!]
This was a long while back.

178
00:07:27,886 --> 00:07:30,541
Everyone would clock in with a cup of coffee,

179
00:07:30,541 --> 00:07:33,066
and if you skipped coffee,
they'd give you the weirdest look.

180
00:07:33,066 --> 00:07:35,138
Like, why isn't that kid drinking coffee?

181
00:07:35,138 --> 00:07:38,072
[A bit much for rookie Sam, that culture]
That whole weird vibe really got to me.

182
00:07:38,072 --> 00:07:42,132
I wanted in on the coffee chats so badly.

183
00:07:42,132 --> 00:07:45,324
[One bold sip of coffee, and...]
Took one sip and my heart was racing.

184
00:07:45,324 --> 00:07:48,105
So from then on, every morning before work,

185
00:07:48,105 --> 00:07:49,944
I started practicing drinking coffee.

186
00:07:49,944 --> 00:07:53,898
After a week or two of that,
when I drank with them,

187
00:07:53,898 --> 00:07:57,906
my heart still raced,
but I'd built up a tolerance.

188
00:07:57,906 --> 00:07:59,605
That's how I picked up the coffee habit.

189
00:07:59,605 --> 00:08:03,074
So I'd make my presence known,
like, hey I'm here,

190
00:08:03,074 --> 00:08:06,777
[Coffee social life, traded for a racing heart]
and they actually liked it even more.

191
00:08:06,777 --> 00:08:08,505
These days you can't live without coffee.

192
00:08:08,505 --> 00:08:10,685
I put in tons of practice
before heading to work.

193
00:08:10,685 --> 00:08:12,439
I'd hit up coffee shops in other neighborhoods,

194
00:08:12,439 --> 00:08:15,606
[Cafe runs before work, the rookie routine]
train up, then go in and drink it down.

195
00:08:15,606 --> 00:08:18,904
So how do today's rookies strike you?

196
00:08:18,904 --> 00:08:19,918
[Glance]

197
00:08:19,918 --> 00:08:22,147
You're constantly checking his vibe, huh?

198
00:08:23,461 --> 00:08:25,863
It's like sometimes the older folks,

199
00:08:25,863 --> 00:08:27,910
watching baseball
or soccer national team games,

200
00:08:27,910 --> 00:08:30,738
they say stuff like,
the older folks next to me,

201
00:08:30,738 --> 00:08:32,938
these guys don't want it bad enough.

202
00:08:32,938 --> 00:08:34,139
That kind of vibe, you know?

203
00:08:34,139 --> 00:08:36,359
I think I finally get
where those older folks are coming from.

204
00:08:36,359 --> 00:08:39,706
With the mindset that if this falls through,
I'm done for,

205
00:08:39,706 --> 00:08:42,446
I'd tough it out wherever I landed.

206
00:08:42,446 --> 00:08:44,381
But nowadays, well...

207
00:08:45,045 --> 00:08:46,584
[Come on]
You keep glancing around nervously.

208
00:08:46,584 --> 00:08:48,165
At this point, maybe turn around and do it.

209
00:08:48,165 --> 00:08:50,054
- Just face the back and shoot.
- He's really watching his step, huh?

210
00:08:50,054 --> 00:08:51,188
[Awkward]

211
00:08:52,356 --> 00:08:54,272
[Owner-chef's neck burns extra today...]

212
00:08:54,272 --> 00:08:56,873
My kids put in real work.

213
00:08:56,873 --> 00:09:01,365
They skip their break
and prep dinner like that.

214
00:09:01,365 --> 00:09:03,968
[Will the local undercover gig pull off?]

215
00:09:03,968 --> 00:09:06,378
At first I had my doubts.

216
00:09:06,378 --> 00:09:08,873
[Rookie to new dish in 5 days]
Getting a dish on the menu,

217
00:09:08,873 --> 00:09:11,809
in a real kitchen, no rookie pulls that off.

218
00:09:11,809 --> 00:09:15,405
You need at least a year in
before anyone hears you out.

219
00:09:15,405 --> 00:09:16,747
Honestly...

220
00:09:16,747 --> 00:09:18,672
[Not hearing it, huh?]

221
00:09:18,672 --> 00:09:22,253
If I spoke up, the rookies would
probably just walk on by.

222
00:09:22,253 --> 00:09:26,056
In a way, the menu is the chef's territory.

223
00:09:26,056 --> 00:09:30,641
It's not really a place
for a rookie to speak up.

224
00:09:30,641 --> 00:09:32,963
Whether the timing works out physically,

225
00:09:32,963 --> 00:09:34,706
honestly, I'm a little worried.

226
00:09:34,706 --> 00:09:36,400
But still,

227
00:09:37,038 --> 00:09:39,305
nothing is off the table.

228
00:09:39,305 --> 00:09:41,405
If the mission gets ready,

229
00:09:41,405 --> 00:09:45,582
my clock will probably rewind
to my early twenties,

230
00:09:45,582 --> 00:09:48,112
back to when I first walked through that door.

231
00:09:48,112 --> 00:09:50,214
I'll probably flip into that mode.

232
00:09:50,214 --> 00:09:53,184
I'll give it everything
and try to earn some respect.

233
00:09:53,184 --> 00:09:56,295
The region we're headed to...

234
00:09:56,295 --> 00:09:59,478
[Sam Kim's undercover chef spot]

235
00:10:01,192 --> 00:10:05,639
[Where Sam Kim's cooking took root]

236
00:10:05,639 --> 00:10:07,798
- Italy.
- Italy.

237
00:10:08,399 --> 00:10:10,008
[France, Italy, Croatia]
[Rome]

238
00:10:10,692 --> 00:10:13,373
[Italy's top Michelin spot, Emilia-Romagna]
It's packed with Michelin spots.

239
00:10:13,373 --> 00:10:14,638
There's serious money

240
00:10:14,638 --> 00:10:17,441
[A region rolling in wealth from day one!]
in Emilia-Romagna, just for starters.

241
00:10:17,441 --> 00:10:20,511
[They call this town a foodie mecca]

242
00:10:21,435 --> 00:10:22,313
Parma, huh?

243
00:10:22,313 --> 00:10:24,353
- Parma?
- Parma.

244
00:10:25,049 --> 00:10:27,739
- Parmesan cheese?
- That's the one.

245
00:10:27,739 --> 00:10:29,086
It's not actually Parmesan cheese.

246
00:10:29,086 --> 00:10:30,414
It's Parmigiano Reggiano.

247
00:10:30,414 --> 00:10:32,572
Right, Parmigiano Reggiano.

248
00:10:32,572 --> 00:10:33,916
This place is famous for a reason.

249
00:10:33,916 --> 00:10:37,015
Ham, for one, has to be huge there.

250
00:10:37,772 --> 00:10:40,364
Prosciutto. Prosciutto also comes from Parma.

251
00:10:40,364 --> 00:10:43,842
[Parmesan cheese]

252
00:10:43,842 --> 00:10:44,969
[Fresh pasta and tons of local dishes]

253
00:10:44,969 --> 00:10:46,176
There's fresh pasta too.

254
00:10:46,176 --> 00:10:48,106
The stuffed dumpling kind of pasta.

255
00:10:48,106 --> 00:10:49,607
A real holy land for food.

256
00:10:49,607 --> 00:10:52,743
[Foodies worldwide flock here nonstop]

257
00:10:52,743 --> 00:10:54,111
[Undercover in Parma, feeling ready?]

258
00:10:54,111 --> 00:10:56,172
Yeah, I'd say so.

259
00:10:56,172 --> 00:10:59,292
Their go-to dishes are pretty set, you know.

260
00:10:59,292 --> 00:11:03,220
[Confident about the undercover turf]
So yeah, I can call it to some degree.

261
00:11:05,490 --> 00:11:07,858
[Sam Kim, 27 years deep in the game]
Yeah, I really need to prep hard this time.

262
00:11:07,858 --> 00:11:13,397
[Survival as the rookie in an Italian kitchen]

263
00:11:13,397 --> 00:11:18,102
[Undercover D-1, landed in Parma]

264
00:11:18,102 --> 00:11:21,012
- So you rolled into Parma a day early?
- Yeah.

265
00:11:23,908 --> 00:11:28,031
[Why a day early? Local recon time]

266
00:11:29,230 --> 00:11:32,272
Today's my chance to just talk my head off.

267
00:11:32,272 --> 00:11:34,539
Starting tomorrow, my mouth's basically shut.

268
00:11:34,539 --> 00:11:36,853
Let it all out today then.

269
00:11:37,821 --> 00:11:39,896
I dug through everything
I could find on that spot.

270
00:11:39,896 --> 00:11:42,826
[Undercover spot, recon done]
- The restaurant? - You did your homework too.

271
00:11:42,826 --> 00:11:44,929
So I scrolled through some reviews,

272
00:11:44,929 --> 00:11:46,998
and the same thing kept popping up.

273
00:11:46,998 --> 00:11:50,267
A ton of them said
it's strictly a locals' spot.

274
00:11:50,267 --> 00:11:51,820
[Real local favorite, hands down]

275
00:11:51,820 --> 00:11:54,004
[Food was amazing, but it's all locals]

276
00:11:54,004 --> 00:11:57,555
[Intel 1: True local-only hidden gem]

277
00:11:57,555 --> 00:11:59,305
And looking it over,

278
00:11:59,305 --> 00:12:01,272
no clue how big the place actually is,

279
00:12:01,272 --> 00:12:03,375
but the menu's pretty packed.

280
00:12:03,375 --> 00:12:06,083
Pheasants are there, guinea fowl too,
all kinds of stuff.

281
00:12:06,083 --> 00:12:11,272
[Intel 2: Wild ingredients, deep local dishes]

282
00:12:11,272 --> 00:12:13,576
So they've got pheasant on there.

283
00:12:13,576 --> 00:12:15,859
I'm pretty curious, honestly.

284
00:12:16,895 --> 00:12:18,429
Austria...

285
00:12:18,429 --> 00:12:20,403
[Tonight's meal is recon for undercover too]
That looks good.

286
00:12:20,403 --> 00:12:23,404
In this region,
a lot of the food kind of overlaps.

287
00:12:23,404 --> 00:12:24,924
Yeah, it overlaps a lot. That's Italy for you.

288
00:12:24,924 --> 00:12:28,304
So before heading in,
I wanted to taste what the vibe is like.

289
00:12:28,304 --> 00:12:29,684
Oh, so it's not where you're actually working.

290
00:12:29,684 --> 00:12:32,443
- Just stopping in to eat then.
- This one's just a stop along the way?

291
00:12:32,443 --> 00:12:34,279
[Heading into a Parma test restaurant]

292
00:12:34,279 --> 00:12:36,379
Oh, must be one of the good ones.

293
00:12:37,482 --> 00:12:39,248
Hello there.

294
00:12:42,270 --> 00:12:46,423
[Almost every table, prosciutto and fried bread]
The ham's running the show here.

295
00:12:47,591 --> 00:12:50,745
[Tasting it like a real Parma local...]

296
00:12:50,745 --> 00:12:52,546
Lard's what makes it taste right.

297
00:12:52,546 --> 00:12:54,466
[Fried bread, lard's the secret]
There's a little bit of it in here.

298
00:12:54,466 --> 00:12:55,899
You can pick it up from the smell.

299
00:12:55,899 --> 00:12:57,735
[Yum]

300
00:12:57,735 --> 00:13:01,271
[Now scanning the dining room]

301
00:13:02,239 --> 00:13:03,874
[Swish]

302
00:13:03,874 --> 00:13:05,375
[Swish]

303
00:13:06,224 --> 00:13:09,880
The staffs here move quickly on their feet.

304
00:13:09,880 --> 00:13:12,305
I really like that.

305
00:13:12,305 --> 00:13:14,851
[Still can't shake the owner-chef brain...]
- Slow workers? They're out. - We never even...

306
00:13:15,720 --> 00:13:16,854
You all set, then?

307
00:13:16,854 --> 00:13:18,504
[Ready to go back to kitchen rookie life?]

308
00:13:18,504 --> 00:13:20,539
Still warming up over here.

309
00:13:20,539 --> 00:13:24,585
Truthfully, recipes and prep work
don't really stress me out.

310
00:13:24,585 --> 00:13:26,697
The process is pretty much the same anyway.

311
00:13:26,697 --> 00:13:30,113
Tomorrow's all about reading the room.

312
00:13:30,113 --> 00:13:32,605
Which rope do I grab onto? That's the thing...

313
00:13:32,605 --> 00:13:34,439
Over there.

314
00:13:34,439 --> 00:13:36,605
- Right, who you stick with.
- You've got to pick the right line.

315
00:13:36,605 --> 00:13:37,806
Picking the right line, yeah.

316
00:13:37,806 --> 00:13:39,272
- For real.
- In the kitchen, the line matters.

317
00:13:39,272 --> 00:13:40,437
You really do need to pick right.

318
00:13:40,437 --> 00:13:42,506
Reading what each person's about,

319
00:13:42,506 --> 00:13:44,499
and the flow of the restaurant.

320
00:13:44,499 --> 00:13:48,218
That's how you climb the ladder fast.

321
00:13:48,853 --> 00:13:53,091
Even chopping away, my head's reading the room.

322
00:13:53,091 --> 00:13:55,259
Who do I latch onto? My head's doing the math.

323
00:13:55,259 --> 00:13:58,595
[Who's the rope I grab onto?]

324
00:13:58,595 --> 00:14:04,301
[Walking past Parma Cathedral]

325
00:14:05,102 --> 00:14:10,798
[Drawn toward where the music's coming from]

326
00:14:11,478 --> 00:14:13,367
Oh, there's the maestro!

327
00:14:13,367 --> 00:14:15,078
Over there.

328
00:14:16,814 --> 00:14:20,383
[A street musician playing solo]

329
00:14:22,019 --> 00:14:24,656
[But somehow...]

330
00:14:24,656 --> 00:14:26,627
[It's getting sadder by the second...]
This is getting way too sad.

331
00:14:26,627 --> 00:14:28,992
I wanted to hear something a bit more upbeat.

332
00:14:32,967 --> 00:14:36,987
[Foreshadowing tomorrow's self?]
Feels like the soundtrack for tomorrow.

333
00:14:36,987 --> 00:14:38,736
This guy's setting a grim mood.

334
00:14:38,736 --> 00:14:40,537
- Calm before the storm.
- Yeah.

335
00:14:40,537 --> 00:14:44,475
[Maybe this is the calm before the storm]

336
00:14:44,475 --> 00:14:45,471
[Crash pad for five days as kitchen rookie]

337
00:14:45,471 --> 00:14:47,978
So this is where you're crashing.

338
00:14:47,978 --> 00:14:50,447
[As soon as he walks into the place]

339
00:14:50,447 --> 00:14:54,118
[Stuff hitting the table one by one]

340
00:14:54,118 --> 00:14:57,121
[A full spread of stationery]

341
00:14:57,121 --> 00:15:00,023
[Practically opening a stationery store]

342
00:15:00,023 --> 00:15:02,160
[Colored tape, pencils, pens, three notebooks]
[Enough supplies to fuel a senior cram session]

343
00:15:02,160 --> 00:15:04,128
Whoa, that's insane.

344
00:15:04,128 --> 00:15:07,023
[FYI: Sam Kim's a hardcore stationery nerd]

345
00:15:07,023 --> 00:15:09,193
Is this going to be enough?

346
00:15:11,268 --> 00:15:13,771
[Working on his resume for tomorrow]

347
00:15:13,771 --> 00:15:17,072
[Deep in agony...]

348
00:15:17,072 --> 00:15:24,348
[Agonizing harder
than Beethoven on a melody...]

349
00:15:25,949 --> 00:15:29,152
What's the right way to wrap the ending?

350
00:15:32,723 --> 00:15:39,272
[Over an hour stuck on just the last line]

351
00:15:39,272 --> 00:15:40,297
Got it!

352
00:15:40,297 --> 00:15:41,932
So here it goes.

353
00:15:43,667 --> 00:15:44,873
[And then, down to the closing line]

354
00:15:44,873 --> 00:15:46,603
So...

355
00:15:46,603 --> 00:15:52,590
[After wrapping up that heartfelt fake resume]

356
00:15:54,778 --> 00:15:56,981
[The next morning came around]

357
00:15:56,981 --> 00:15:58,481
Hey, finally.

358
00:15:59,583 --> 00:16:02,630
[Rookie's undercover job hunt]
[D-DAY]

359
00:16:03,687 --> 00:16:07,057
[Coloreto Village in Parma]

360
00:16:07,057 --> 00:16:09,205
- Like, a bit on the out... outside.
- The outskirts.

361
00:16:09,205 --> 00:16:11,361
[Commute cutting through green fields]
A bit tucked away on the outskirts.

362
00:16:11,361 --> 00:16:13,231
[First undercover day, any nerves?]

363
00:16:13,231 --> 00:16:15,999
Honestly, I'm not nervous.

364
00:16:15,999 --> 00:16:17,552
[Did you finish the resume?]

365
00:16:17,552 --> 00:16:19,370
This resume might...

366
00:16:19,370 --> 00:16:20,807
actually make you cry!

367
00:16:20,807 --> 00:16:23,172
Once you see my resume, seriously...

368
00:16:23,172 --> 00:16:26,043
[The final line, born of long suffering]
I want to take the first step

369
00:16:26,043 --> 00:16:28,692
toward my dream right here.

370
00:16:28,692 --> 00:16:30,615
That line would hook

371
00:16:30,615 --> 00:16:33,249
any owner!

372
00:16:33,249 --> 00:16:35,053
I've got other lines ready too.

373
00:16:35,053 --> 00:16:37,287
If you hire me,

374
00:16:37,287 --> 00:16:39,806
I think I'd be really happy.

375
00:16:39,806 --> 00:16:40,824
Oh, lines like that are great!

376
00:16:40,824 --> 00:16:42,593
- That's slick.
- Right?

377
00:16:42,593 --> 00:16:45,124
So if that resume landed at your restaurant,
instant hire?

378
00:16:45,124 --> 00:16:46,663
Instant hire.

379
00:16:47,706 --> 00:16:48,799
Pulling on the heartstrings.

380
00:16:48,799 --> 00:16:51,320
[Beyond the all-nighter resume...]

381
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:55,322
Honestly, the day before, I was a bit worried.

382
00:16:55,322 --> 00:16:57,038
What if I can't catch what they're saying?

383
00:16:57,038 --> 00:16:58,653
[A bit of Italian study too]
The language barrier and all.

384
00:16:58,653 --> 00:17:00,544
Will this work out? Stuff like that.

385
00:17:00,544 --> 00:17:02,280
[Worn out]

386
00:17:02,280 --> 00:17:07,217
Just running a simulation in my head
about what I would say

387
00:17:07,217 --> 00:17:09,472
[After memorizing every possible exchange]
when meeting these imaginary people.

388
00:17:09,472 --> 00:17:11,889
So, I started writing it all down.

389
00:17:11,889 --> 00:17:16,483
[Could I use the bathroom?]
[Could I get some water?]

390
00:17:16,483 --> 00:17:18,428
As soon as I stepped out and started walking,

391
00:17:18,428 --> 00:17:20,430
surprisingly, I felt great.

392
00:17:20,430 --> 00:17:22,432
[Pulled an all-nighter prepping,
but feeling good about day one!]

393
00:17:24,801 --> 00:17:25,669
[That a white shirt?]

394
00:17:25,669 --> 00:17:27,470
Must work there.

395
00:17:28,893 --> 00:17:31,141
That's the chef?

396
00:17:34,311 --> 00:17:37,508
[Around the back?]

397
00:17:38,516 --> 00:17:40,050
This is it.

398
00:17:41,986 --> 00:17:43,038
Nerves kick in right there.

399
00:17:43,038 --> 00:17:45,422
- Totally rattled.
- Same, I was shaking.

400
00:17:46,223 --> 00:17:49,276
[Door still locked tight]

401
00:17:53,597 --> 00:17:56,494
[Sam Kim trailing behind, reading the room]

402
00:17:59,506 --> 00:18:02,460
[Voices getting closer]

403
00:18:02,460 --> 00:18:04,038
The thing I worried about most

404
00:18:04,038 --> 00:18:06,781
was the first impression.

405
00:18:06,781 --> 00:18:08,339
What if the vibe

406
00:18:08,339 --> 00:18:11,481
came off cold, you know?

407
00:18:13,016 --> 00:18:14,405
That him?

408
00:18:14,405 --> 00:18:15,919
Huh?

409
00:18:17,271 --> 00:18:18,355
Morning.

410
00:18:18,355 --> 00:18:19,390
[That winning fang grin]

411
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:21,625
Morning.

412
00:18:21,625 --> 00:18:23,226
Hey.

413
00:18:23,860 --> 00:18:25,226
[Warm greeting]
- Hey. - Hey there.

414
00:18:25,226 --> 00:18:26,539
Morning.

415
00:18:26,539 --> 00:18:28,565
[Awkward little wave]
- Morning. - Hi.

416
00:18:28,565 --> 00:18:30,472
I'm...

417
00:18:30,472 --> 00:18:33,631
Hee Tae, coming in from Seoul.

418
00:18:33,631 --> 00:18:36,371
- Hee Tae, coming in from Seoul.
- Your Italian is sharp.

419
00:18:36,371 --> 00:18:37,745
Pleasure.

420
00:18:37,745 --> 00:18:40,444
Here's my resume.

421
00:18:40,444 --> 00:18:41,446
Okay.

422
00:18:41,446 --> 00:18:43,706
Stuck to the script.

423
00:18:43,706 --> 00:18:46,405
- Acting.
- Played out just like I pictured it.

424
00:18:46,405 --> 00:18:48,585
[Drawing on those Pasta drama chops...]
This line right here.

425
00:18:48,585 --> 00:18:51,088
So I just hit the button.

426
00:18:51,088 --> 00:18:54,227
[All that overnight Italian paying off]

427
00:18:54,227 --> 00:18:57,060
[Playback mode, word for word]
Here's my resume.

428
00:18:57,060 --> 00:18:58,539
Okay.

429
00:18:58,539 --> 00:19:00,339
[Still sorting out who's who]
Gianpietro, that's me.

430
00:19:00,339 --> 00:19:01,332
Simone.

431
00:19:01,332 --> 00:19:02,572
Simone.

432
00:19:02,572 --> 00:19:04,468
- Elisabetta.
- Elisabetta.

433
00:19:04,468 --> 00:19:06,906
- Lucrezia.
- Lucrezia.

434
00:19:06,906 --> 00:19:09,847
All right, now we just
wait on Giancarlo to open up.

435
00:19:09,847 --> 00:19:14,517
[Sudden confession]
My Italian isn't great.

436
00:19:16,113 --> 00:19:17,355
Mine isn't either.

437
00:19:17,355 --> 00:19:19,706
[Gestures it's all good]
Sounds perfect to me.

438
00:19:19,706 --> 00:19:21,351
Okay.

439
00:19:21,351 --> 00:19:26,189
Once Giancarlo unlocks the door,
we grab a coffee.

440
00:19:26,189 --> 00:19:26,939
[Grateful]
Okay.

441
00:19:26,939 --> 00:19:28,772
- Okay.
- Thanks.

442
00:19:28,772 --> 00:19:32,162
- Got this warm read on him right away.
- For real.

443
00:19:33,072 --> 00:19:35,899
They were stuck out there too,
waiting on somebody

444
00:19:35,899 --> 00:19:38,136
to unlock the place.

445
00:19:38,136 --> 00:19:42,238
Even so, they made me feel really welcome.

446
00:19:42,843 --> 00:19:44,239
Pretty cool.

447
00:19:44,239 --> 00:19:45,764
Looks like a letter.

448
00:19:45,764 --> 00:19:48,111
It's not perfect or anything.

449
00:19:48,111 --> 00:19:50,280
[Sneaks a peek]

450
00:19:51,239 --> 00:19:53,216
[Swoosh]

451
00:19:53,987 --> 00:19:56,953
- Can't I read it?
- No, you can't!

452
00:19:58,806 --> 00:20:00,447
- There you go again.
- Nope.

453
00:20:00,447 --> 00:20:01,658
Curious one, huh.

454
00:20:01,658 --> 00:20:02,788
Yeah, I want a look too.

455
00:20:02,788 --> 00:20:03,768
- Nope.
- Really, no?

456
00:20:03,768 --> 00:20:06,423
- Okay.
- First dibs go to me.

457
00:20:06,423 --> 00:20:09,105
[Center of attention]
Everyone of them wanted a peek at that resume.

458
00:20:09,105 --> 00:20:09,933
[The name]
Heh?

459
00:20:09,933 --> 00:20:11,305
- Hee.
- Hee?

460
00:20:11,305 --> 00:20:12,904
- Hee Tae.
- Hee Tae.

461
00:20:12,904 --> 00:20:13,939
- Hee Tae.
- That's it.

462
00:20:13,939 --> 00:20:14,806
Okay.

463
00:20:14,806 --> 00:20:16,106
- His name's Hee Tae.
- Hee Tae.

464
00:20:16,106 --> 00:20:17,209
- Oh, real name!
- The name is...

465
00:20:17,209 --> 00:20:18,809
- Went with his actual name.
- Yeah, Hee Tae.

466
00:20:18,809 --> 00:20:20,207
[Sam Kim's undercover alias is Hee Tae]

467
00:20:20,207 --> 00:20:22,245
Pulled it off in Italian, all of it.

468
00:20:22,245 --> 00:20:23,914
Of course.

469
00:20:23,914 --> 00:20:26,441
[Inching closer]

470
00:20:27,634 --> 00:20:28,919
[Swoosh]

471
00:20:28,919 --> 00:20:30,754
Okay. Never mind.

472
00:20:30,754 --> 00:20:32,139
You're the worst, you know that?

473
00:20:32,139 --> 00:20:33,405
I'm just curious.

474
00:20:33,405 --> 00:20:34,606
Yeah, I get it.

475
00:20:34,606 --> 00:20:36,146
I know.

476
00:20:36,146 --> 00:20:37,365
Curious type, isn't she?

477
00:20:37,365 --> 00:20:39,830
Big time.

478
00:20:39,830 --> 00:20:42,940
[Undercover rookie Hee Tae clocked in,
9:00 AM]

479
00:20:44,984 --> 00:20:48,478
[Someone showing up right on the dot]
The boss has arrived.

480
00:20:49,806 --> 00:20:52,909
[The boss?]
- Hello. - Hello.

481
00:20:53,577 --> 00:20:54,911
Let's head inside.

482
00:20:54,911 --> 00:20:56,980
The owner was already in there?

483
00:20:56,980 --> 00:21:00,016
- Seriously?
- Funny enough, the owner rolls in last.

484
00:21:00,016 --> 00:21:01,718
[Owner unlocks right at start time]
So everyone shows up on the dot here?

485
00:21:01,718 --> 00:21:03,878
[Coming early gets you nowhere]
Right on the dot!

486
00:21:03,878 --> 00:21:06,022
Inside, inside.

487
00:21:06,022 --> 00:21:07,322
- Please.
- Thank you.

488
00:21:07,322 --> 00:21:11,108
[Still a little dazed,
stepping into the undercover restaurant!]

489
00:21:14,097 --> 00:21:18,477
[Looking around...]

490
00:21:18,477 --> 00:21:19,889
Whoa!

491
00:21:22,305 --> 00:21:25,475
[Finally getting a real look
at the undercover restaurant]

492
00:21:29,212 --> 00:21:30,981
This is great, totally a real local spot.

493
00:21:30,981 --> 00:21:32,282
That red checkered pattern.

494
00:21:32,282 --> 00:21:34,084
[Red checkered tables,
classic Italian local joint]

495
00:21:34,084 --> 00:21:39,823
[The two running this old-world restaurant]

496
00:21:39,823 --> 00:21:41,825
Gianpietro, that's me,

497
00:21:41,825 --> 00:21:43,994
45 years old.

498
00:21:43,994 --> 00:21:47,792
This year marks 30 years in the kitchen for me.

499
00:21:49,432 --> 00:21:52,569
[Head Chef Gianpietro,
number one in the kitchen]

500
00:21:52,569 --> 00:21:54,538
The name's Giancarlo.

501
00:21:54,538 --> 00:21:57,574
Together with Gianpietro, this restaurant

502
00:21:57,574 --> 00:22:00,484
is something we've been running for 20 years.

503
00:22:01,545 --> 00:22:04,281
[Owner Giancarlo]
This owner used to be a chef.

504
00:22:04,281 --> 00:22:06,349
[Former 2-star chef]

505
00:22:06,349 --> 00:22:08,084
He's bound to be strict.

506
00:22:09,052 --> 00:22:11,221
[Gianpietro and Giancarlo's restaurant]

507
00:22:11,221 --> 00:22:14,958
We weren't the ones who opened this place.

508
00:22:14,958 --> 00:22:17,093
The truth is, this restaurant has been around

509
00:22:17,093 --> 00:22:21,025
for well over 100 years already.

510
00:22:22,032 --> 00:22:25,415
It's a deeply rooted Parma institution.

511
00:22:26,878 --> 00:22:28,350
They call it the two trees, and sure enough

512
00:22:28,350 --> 00:22:30,507
- there's just two, really pretty.
- That one too...

513
00:22:30,507 --> 00:22:32,724
Those are pushing 100 years easy.

514
00:22:32,724 --> 00:22:36,646
[So the restaurant's original name actually
means 'The Two Plane Trees']

515
00:22:36,646 --> 00:22:41,285
November of 2005 was
when we took over this restaurant.

516
00:22:43,126 --> 00:22:45,889
And the long-standing values of this place,

517
00:22:45,889 --> 00:22:50,560
we made it our mission
to preserve them as they are.

518
00:22:50,560 --> 00:22:53,098
[Ever since the two took the reins]

519
00:22:53,897 --> 00:22:58,568
[Listed in the Michelin Guide
every year since 2013]

520
00:22:59,236 --> 00:23:01,884
This restaurant is already crazy famous
on its own.

521
00:23:01,884 --> 00:23:03,473
[A pilgrimage spot drawing foodies
from all over Italy]

522
00:23:03,473 --> 00:23:06,877
[Meet the restaurant's kitchen crew]
I'm the head chef, the number one...

523
00:23:06,877 --> 00:23:10,113
and inside the kitchen group,
there's Lucrezia and Simone.

524
00:23:10,113 --> 00:23:14,684
Simone, you could say, is the key guy.

525
00:23:14,684 --> 00:23:18,321
He's like my second pair of eyes and arms.

526
00:23:18,321 --> 00:23:21,925
Because Simone, he gives me that peace of mind.

527
00:23:21,925 --> 00:23:24,861
[Sous Chef Simone, number two]

528
00:23:24,861 --> 00:23:29,299
Lucrezia, I'd say she has
this really methodical streak about her.

529
00:23:29,299 --> 00:23:31,880
Whatever task you hand her, she'll get it done,

530
00:23:31,880 --> 00:23:35,705
someone you can really count on.

531
00:23:35,705 --> 00:23:38,275
- From where I'm sitting, she's the key player.
- The youngest one.

532
00:23:38,275 --> 00:23:40,934
- A real key player.
- So she's good at her job.

533
00:23:40,934 --> 00:23:44,567
[Lucrezia, the do-it-all number three]

534
00:23:44,567 --> 00:23:46,816
[Curious about the new rookie joining them?]

535
00:23:46,816 --> 00:23:49,452
The thing I want to ask him is...

536
00:23:49,452 --> 00:23:51,320
I want to ask him 'why.'

537
00:23:52,355 --> 00:23:57,827
This is something we need to know.

538
00:23:57,827 --> 00:24:03,667
Whether he's ready
to handle the work of a kitchen.

539
00:24:03,667 --> 00:24:08,772
If we see that he's unsure about the work,

540
00:24:08,772 --> 00:24:13,777
or is showing any hesitation
in what he's doing,

541
00:24:13,777 --> 00:24:16,313
while the rest of us are working,

542
00:24:16,313 --> 00:24:19,816
he might as well just stand in the corner.

543
00:24:19,816 --> 00:24:24,721
I'll be straight with him
and tell him to quit and find something else.

544
00:24:24,721 --> 00:24:26,756
This work is never easy.

545
00:24:27,757 --> 00:24:29,092
This guy's scary.

546
00:24:29,092 --> 00:24:31,127
I'm running. Count me out.

547
00:24:31,127 --> 00:24:33,730
[Person of interest: Owner Gianca]
That owner there is seriously sharp!

548
00:24:33,730 --> 00:24:35,932
- Even more genuine about it.
- He's incredibly sharp.

549
00:24:35,932 --> 00:24:40,549
I want to see the face of the guy
who thinks he can handle our kitchen.

550
00:24:42,973 --> 00:24:44,432
They're actually terrifying.

551
00:24:44,432 --> 00:24:48,144
[Oblivious to the brutal pressure waiting...]

552
00:24:48,144 --> 00:24:49,546
[Resume gets handed over to the owner]
Come in.

553
00:24:49,546 --> 00:24:51,839
- I'm Giancarlo.
- Nice to meet you.

554
00:24:51,839 --> 00:24:53,404
Okay.

555
00:24:55,018 --> 00:24:56,853
[Chef Sam Kim, what kind of cover story
did he put on that resume?]

556
00:24:56,853 --> 00:24:59,849
I'm dying to know what's on that resume.

557
00:25:01,358 --> 00:25:02,826
You work in farming?

558
00:25:02,826 --> 00:25:03,860
Uh... yes!

559
00:25:03,860 --> 00:25:05,729
- Really? Still doing it now?
- Yes.

560
00:25:05,729 --> 00:25:08,231
You told them you do farming?

561
00:25:08,231 --> 00:25:09,799
Is this an olive tree?

562
00:25:09,799 --> 00:25:12,602
- Olives?
- Olives, yes! Back in Korea.

563
00:25:12,602 --> 00:25:14,838
- In Korea?
- Yes.

564
00:25:14,838 --> 00:25:16,706
[Sam Kim's undercover identity]

565
00:25:16,706 --> 00:25:18,041
[Name: Kim Hee Tae]

566
00:25:18,041 --> 00:25:21,511
[And now, an olive farmer apparently...]

567
00:25:21,511 --> 00:25:23,480
- Olive farming in Korea?
- What?

568
00:25:23,480 --> 00:25:25,048
- There aren't any olive trees in Korea, right?
- No, but actually...

569
00:25:25,048 --> 00:25:26,549
[A backstory he really thought through]
There actually are some, on Jeju Island.

570
00:25:26,549 --> 00:25:28,785
- Oh, so they do exist.
- Right, they do exist.

571
00:25:28,785 --> 00:25:31,354
[Real photos from when he actually
farmed a few years back]

572
00:25:31,354 --> 00:25:34,157
[Add some AI magic,
and boom, instant cover story]

573
00:25:34,157 --> 00:25:38,528
[Picked olives because he knows them well,
just in case his cover gets blown!]

574
00:25:38,528 --> 00:25:41,598
[Politely]
Have you ever cooked Italian food before?

575
00:25:41,598 --> 00:25:43,400
- A little.
- A little?

576
00:25:43,400 --> 00:25:45,869
[Disguise info crafted for going undercover]
- A little. - A little? Okay.

577
00:25:45,869 --> 00:25:50,807
[And so... an interview kicks off
with lies mixed in with the truth...]

578
00:25:50,807 --> 00:25:54,377
My mother is a chef! That's right.

579
00:25:54,377 --> 00:25:55,545
[This part is true]

580
00:25:55,545 --> 00:25:57,480
Back when I was a little kid,

581
00:25:57,480 --> 00:25:59,049
I helped out my mom with her cooking work.

582
00:25:59,049 --> 00:26:00,683
Yes, you already know...

583
00:26:00,683 --> 00:26:03,820
[Pulling out the chef mom story
to flex a bit of cooking cred]

584
00:26:03,820 --> 00:26:07,456
[Other tidbits crammed into that packed resume]

585
00:26:08,425 --> 00:26:10,793
[I'm a "farmer," and...]

586
00:26:11,628 --> 00:26:15,265
["Korea's olive oil evangelist,"
a celebrity with farming roots]

587
00:26:15,265 --> 00:26:17,710
[After tossing out this convincing info]

588
00:26:18,835 --> 00:26:22,005
If you gave me

589
00:26:22,005 --> 00:26:25,308
the chance...

590
00:26:25,308 --> 00:26:27,644
to work here,

591
00:26:27,644 --> 00:26:30,480
it'd make me happy every single day.

592
00:26:30,480 --> 00:26:32,382
Please.

593
00:26:32,382 --> 00:26:34,084
[Owner's touched]

594
00:26:34,084 --> 00:26:35,618
Okay.

595
00:26:35,618 --> 00:26:37,720
[Delivers the heartfelt line he had ready]
No. Don't worry.

596
00:26:39,222 --> 00:26:41,424
For that rookie spot, I really...

597
00:26:41,424 --> 00:26:42,859
- Hey, that kind of line.
- A little bit...

598
00:26:42,859 --> 00:26:44,639
When you stumble through it from the heart,

599
00:26:44,639 --> 00:26:46,596
- it lands so much harder somehow.
- Exactly.

600
00:26:46,596 --> 00:26:49,065
- And he went Italian instead of English.
- For sure.

601
00:26:49,065 --> 00:26:52,268
The first impression turned out really solid.

602
00:26:52,268 --> 00:26:55,305
His intro was on point too.

603
00:26:55,305 --> 00:26:57,140
I thought it was great.

604
00:26:57,140 --> 00:27:00,689
Our world runs on a whole lot of passion.

605
00:27:00,689 --> 00:27:01,911
[Owner totally moved]
Passion above everything else!

606
00:27:01,911 --> 00:27:04,681
Whatever passion you pour in,

607
00:27:04,681 --> 00:27:07,617
[Hee Tae's passion line that worked worldwide]
that's exactly what you get back.

608
00:27:07,617 --> 00:27:09,185
Hit every beat of the script this morning.

609
00:27:09,185 --> 00:27:11,488
[Stuck to the plan all the way through!]

610
00:27:12,455 --> 00:27:13,756
[The satisfying moment in the interview]

611
00:27:13,756 --> 00:27:15,091
Okay.

612
00:27:15,091 --> 00:27:17,460
Go change into your uniform,

613
00:27:17,460 --> 00:27:18,928
- and we're starting!
- Yes.

614
00:27:18,928 --> 00:27:21,664
Thank you so much!

615
00:27:21,664 --> 00:27:23,399
- Got it.
- Thank you.

616
00:27:23,399 --> 00:27:25,522
[First impression nailed it]

617
00:27:27,837 --> 00:27:30,447
So this is where it actually begins!

618
00:27:31,374 --> 00:27:33,676
Lu...

619
00:27:33,676 --> 00:27:35,011
- Simone!
- Simone!

620
00:27:35,011 --> 00:27:37,480
- Hee Tae.
- Simone!

621
00:27:37,480 --> 00:27:39,248
Lu, Simone!

622
00:27:39,916 --> 00:27:43,500
[Finally stepping into the kitchen]

623
00:27:44,254 --> 00:27:46,589
[Riiip?]

624
00:27:47,857 --> 00:27:50,619
[Batman]

625
00:27:51,729 --> 00:27:55,665
[What's with that bread cap on his head?]

626
00:27:55,665 --> 00:27:59,936
[The rookie cap handed to Hee Tae today]

627
00:27:59,936 --> 00:28:01,046
Does it look okay?

628
00:28:01,046 --> 00:28:03,737
[Getting the okay from the No. 2 senior]

629
00:28:04,434 --> 00:28:07,377
[Rookie Hee Tae locked and loaded]

630
00:28:07,377 --> 00:28:08,278
I take it from the door,

631
00:28:08,278 --> 00:28:11,214
[Truth is, this place...]
of course, we have that space too.

632
00:28:11,214 --> 00:28:13,816
[A kitchen where stations
are split clean by rank]

633
00:28:13,816 --> 00:28:15,350
[Gianpietro, No. 1]
[Simone, No. 2]

634
00:28:15,350 --> 00:28:18,105
[Lucrezia, No. 3]

635
00:28:18,888 --> 00:28:22,753
[Lucrezia's station: fresh pasta production]

636
00:28:29,098 --> 00:28:34,404
[Simone's station: appetizers]

637
00:28:38,942 --> 00:28:43,947
[Gianpietro's station: pasta and mains]

638
00:28:43,947 --> 00:28:45,481
[Mains, appetizers, fresh pasta production]

639
00:28:45,481 --> 00:28:50,529
[The stages Hee Tae has five days to clear]

640
00:28:51,454 --> 00:28:53,022
[Let's roll]
Okay.

641
00:28:55,024 --> 00:28:56,793
Here's what you're going to do now.

642
00:28:56,793 --> 00:28:58,394
You'll be with Lucrezia today,

643
00:28:58,394 --> 00:29:02,198
making yellow pasta, green pasta,

644
00:29:02,198 --> 00:29:03,399
and some gelato.

645
00:29:03,399 --> 00:29:05,668
[First rookie assignment handed out]
- Got it? - Yes.

646
00:29:05,668 --> 00:29:07,670
[Wash those hands first]

647
00:29:07,670 --> 00:29:08,938
Okay.

648
00:29:08,938 --> 00:29:12,909
[Step one of the dough: cracking eggs]
Crack 15 whole,

649
00:29:12,909 --> 00:29:15,978
and for 15 more, just the yolks in.

650
00:29:18,548 --> 00:29:21,544
[That's several trays of eggs to crack solo]

651
00:29:25,488 --> 00:29:27,363
[Quick glance]

652
00:29:28,891 --> 00:29:31,026
[Another glance]

653
00:29:32,495 --> 00:29:38,301
[Eyes watching from every corner]

654
00:29:38,301 --> 00:29:41,738
[Status check on the rookie]

655
00:29:41,738 --> 00:29:43,406
[How's the first rookie task going?]

656
00:29:43,406 --> 00:29:45,107
Cracking eggs?

657
00:29:45,708 --> 00:29:50,046
A handful of eggs... I mean, just a few...

658
00:29:50,046 --> 00:29:53,583
honestly, I mean...

659
00:29:53,583 --> 00:29:54,917
it was easy!

660
00:29:54,917 --> 00:29:58,061
"Huh? Am I really allowed
to breeze through this?"

661
00:30:00,857 --> 00:30:04,027
[Right when it looked
like smooth sailing for the rookie]

662
00:30:04,027 --> 00:30:05,295
Where is he?

663
00:30:05,295 --> 00:30:07,297
- Who?
- The new arrival.

664
00:30:07,297 --> 00:30:08,499
Right here.

665
00:30:11,134 --> 00:30:15,408
[Enter the owner]

666
00:30:15,408 --> 00:30:17,939
Doing all right?

667
00:30:17,939 --> 00:30:19,402
Yes.

668
00:30:23,046 --> 00:30:24,747
What's with the spoon?

669
00:30:25,715 --> 00:30:27,249
Shell?

670
00:30:29,152 --> 00:30:32,506
[A piece of eggshell, spotted by the owner]

671
00:30:32,506 --> 00:30:34,425
The shell, I was actually about to fish it out,

672
00:30:34,425 --> 00:30:37,572
but he just walks over and scoops it right out.

673
00:30:37,572 --> 00:30:39,461
Yeah, thank you.

674
00:30:41,299 --> 00:30:43,091
You dropped that in on purpose, right?
That doesn't usually go in.

675
00:30:43,091 --> 00:30:45,601
No. I saw it land in there
and was about to grab it.

676
00:30:45,601 --> 00:30:47,025
- He clocked it immediately.
- Immediately.

677
00:30:47,025 --> 00:30:49,465
He really catches that stuff, impressive.

678
00:30:49,465 --> 00:30:52,915
Being a former chef,
of course... he's bound to step in.

679
00:30:56,205 --> 00:30:59,205
Walking by, I noticed a piece of eggshell

680
00:30:59,205 --> 00:31:02,285
dropped into another egg.

681
00:31:02,285 --> 00:31:05,822
It's day one,
plus it's not really his main station,

682
00:31:05,822 --> 00:31:07,523
so I'll let it slide.

683
00:31:07,523 --> 00:31:12,395
The key thing is that there was no bad intent.

684
00:31:12,395 --> 00:31:15,996
I was sitting there thinking,
"Why is this guy watching my every move?"

685
00:31:15,996 --> 00:31:17,056
- The owner, he just...
- He's anxious.

686
00:31:17,056 --> 00:31:18,316
- From an owner's standpoint...
- He has to watch.

687
00:31:18,316 --> 00:31:20,570
- Picture a farmer rolling into your kitchen.
- Right.

688
00:31:20,570 --> 00:31:22,956
He keeps swinging by,
striking up conversation every chance he gets,

689
00:31:22,956 --> 00:31:25,708
constantly checking in,
and it just keeps going.

690
00:31:25,708 --> 00:31:28,044
- I was like, what a peculiar owner.
- Of course he's anxious.

691
00:31:28,044 --> 00:31:29,912
[Please ease up on the farmer fascination...]

692
00:31:29,912 --> 00:31:34,250
[One eggshell, and the tension creeps in fast]

693
00:31:34,250 --> 00:31:37,706
[Eyes still locked on]

694
00:31:39,322 --> 00:31:42,379
[And whether it's in his head or not...]

695
00:31:45,772 --> 00:31:47,765
Lu, the Gorgonzola's in the fridge.

696
00:31:47,765 --> 00:31:51,968
Stop leaving things all over the place,
set them outside.

697
00:31:51,968 --> 00:31:53,302
- Right?
- Yes.

698
00:31:53,302 --> 00:31:54,944
- I put it.
- Okay.

699
00:31:54,944 --> 00:32:00,282
Bring more vegetables!
This barely scratches the surface.

700
00:32:00,873 --> 00:32:04,272
- And the biscuits aren't out yet, right?
- No...

701
00:32:04,272 --> 00:32:06,172
Lu.

702
00:32:06,172 --> 00:32:10,253
Nothing changes here,
do it the way you do it every day.

703
00:32:10,253 --> 00:32:12,891
[Head chef on full edge]

704
00:32:12,891 --> 00:32:15,537
[Hee Tae's eyes going wide]

705
00:32:15,537 --> 00:32:18,839
[Will day one as a kitchen rookie
survive in one piece?]

706
00:32:18,839 --> 00:32:21,690
[Second up on Undercover Chef]
And here comes another Italian-trained chef.

707
00:32:21,690 --> 00:32:23,170
- I'm really excited for this.
- Same here.

708
00:32:23,170 --> 00:32:24,770
- What's got you excited?
- Kwon Sung Jun.

709
00:32:24,770 --> 00:32:27,038
[Conquering a local restaurant in three days?]
The teaser had it pegged at three days...

710
00:32:27,038 --> 00:32:28,739
- Yeah, that's right.
- What was I even doing on day three?

711
00:32:28,739 --> 00:32:29,610
[Confidence maxed]
You'll see soon enough.

712
00:32:29,610 --> 00:32:32,350
Word is Sung Jun headed off to Naples.

713
00:32:32,350 --> 00:32:33,210
That's right, Naples.

714
00:32:33,210 --> 00:32:34,550
[Code name]
I'm the Napoli Matfia.

715
00:32:34,550 --> 00:32:36,630
You went to Naples last year, too.

716
00:32:36,630 --> 00:32:38,657
I've been over there twice
this year alone already.

717
00:32:38,657 --> 00:32:40,630
- Two trips in the first half of the year.
- Two in the first half.

718
00:32:40,630 --> 00:32:42,472
It's pretty much like working from home.

719
00:32:42,472 --> 00:32:45,447
- What's with the swagger?
- You don't actually work from home, though.

720
00:32:45,447 --> 00:32:46,967
So what I mean is,
it's the same as working in Seoul.

721
00:32:46,967 --> 00:32:48,147
[Naples is... like Seoul...]
Feels like working in Seoul.

722
00:32:48,147 --> 00:32:50,247
That's because Naples is where I worked,
at a fine dining spot.

723
00:32:50,247 --> 00:32:52,667
So out of everyone,
you probably had it the most...

724
00:32:52,667 --> 00:32:54,005
- Right.
- You went in with the comfiest setup.

725
00:32:54,005 --> 00:32:57,687
Pretty much, and honestly, you'll see,
it was all just heads-down work.

726
00:32:57,687 --> 00:32:59,168
So if it's boring, should we just skip it?

727
00:32:59,168 --> 00:33:00,407
- Skip ahead?
- Should we skip?

728
00:33:00,407 --> 00:33:02,937
A minute ago you were
stressing about screen time.

729
00:33:02,937 --> 00:33:05,939
- All right, shall we get to it?
- He's so cocky right now,

730
00:33:05,939 --> 00:33:08,387
- I'm curious to see how he pulled it off.
- Brace yourselves.

731
00:33:08,387 --> 00:33:09,846
Brace yourselves, everyone.

732
00:33:09,846 --> 00:33:11,364
Yes, hello there.

733
00:33:11,364 --> 00:33:13,683
I go by the name Napoli Matfia,

734
00:33:13,683 --> 00:33:15,585
and I'm Chef Kwon Sung Jun.

735
00:33:15,585 --> 00:33:20,122
[The cooking-survival winner everyone knows]

736
00:33:20,122 --> 00:33:21,944
[Feels like ages ago]
I can barely even remember it now.

737
00:33:21,944 --> 00:33:24,760
Anyway, I went and rolled
with a Naples-themed nickname,

738
00:33:24,760 --> 00:33:26,796
took home the win under that name,

739
00:33:26,796 --> 00:33:27,663
[Napoli Matfia]

740
00:33:27,663 --> 00:33:29,165
[A new life kicked off by his win]

741
00:33:30,253 --> 00:33:32,264
[Kicking off with the tiramisu craze]
Haven't seen that in a while.

742
00:33:32,264 --> 00:33:33,804
I think I'm at my busiest right now.

743
00:33:33,804 --> 00:33:36,305
There's a ton of stuff in production lately,

744
00:33:36,305 --> 00:33:37,082
[Commercials]

745
00:33:37,082 --> 00:33:38,743
[TV]
Riding this wave of crazy popularity...

746
00:33:38,743 --> 00:33:40,602
[YouTube]
So there's this winner, Mat-Pizza.

747
00:33:40,602 --> 00:33:42,233
I've really done it all.

748
00:33:45,834 --> 00:33:49,734
[Where every bit of this story all kicked off]

749
00:33:49,734 --> 00:33:52,634
It's the city that flipped
so much around for me,

750
00:33:52,634 --> 00:33:54,671
so I hold a real soft spot for it.

751
00:33:59,068 --> 00:34:00,434
Vesuvius.

752
00:34:00,434 --> 00:34:01,453
Vesuvius.

753
00:34:01,453 --> 00:34:02,367
I'm really curious.

754
00:34:02,367 --> 00:34:04,446
[Napoli, Italy]
A whole different world, right? Naples.

755
00:34:04,446 --> 00:34:07,002
My life took a major turn over there,

756
00:34:07,002 --> 00:34:10,604
so if it's doable, Naples would be
the pick this time around too.

757
00:34:10,604 --> 00:34:15,785
[Back to Chef Kwon's starting line]

758
00:34:19,615 --> 00:34:21,181
- So this is the spot.
- This is what it looks like?

759
00:34:21,181 --> 00:34:23,319
[What was rookie Kwon Sung Jun like?]

760
00:34:23,319 --> 00:34:24,817
Me?

761
00:34:27,287 --> 00:34:29,898
Worked my tail off, I guess, just...

762
00:34:29,898 --> 00:34:33,759
The place I worked was
this island off Naples called Ischia,

763
00:34:33,759 --> 00:34:35,469
and it was a Michelin two-star restaurant.

764
00:34:35,469 --> 00:34:37,296
- Two stars, that's right.
- And that right there is Naples.

765
00:34:37,296 --> 00:34:41,869
That was basically
my first real kitchen experience.

766
00:34:41,869 --> 00:34:44,704
[Sung Jun at 25, his rookie days]
Looking pretty fresh.

767
00:34:44,704 --> 00:34:46,582
You were slim back in the day.

768
00:34:46,582 --> 00:34:48,403
[Rookie Sung Jun's daily grind]
I typically clocked in at 9:00 AM.

769
00:34:48,403 --> 00:34:51,181
and clocked out around 1 in the morning.

770
00:34:51,181 --> 00:34:52,721
That's 16 hours?

771
00:34:52,721 --> 00:34:54,422
Six days a week, what's that come out to?

772
00:34:54,422 --> 00:34:56,401
96 hours a week.

773
00:34:56,401 --> 00:34:58,641
No breaks built in either.

774
00:34:58,641 --> 00:35:02,322
Over there, I mean...
obviously the language was a wall,

775
00:35:02,322 --> 00:35:05,427
and Naples especially has this brutal dialect,

776
00:35:05,427 --> 00:35:07,861
so back then I caught absolute hell.

777
00:35:07,861 --> 00:35:09,496
[Shudders]

778
00:35:09,496 --> 00:35:12,464
In a kitchen, the most critical thing
is communication.

779
00:35:12,464 --> 00:35:15,977
The second talking breaks down, tempers flare.

780
00:35:15,977 --> 00:35:19,269
Every second counts in a kitchen,
service has to fly out the pass,

781
00:35:19,269 --> 00:35:21,205
and they're saying something,
but I can't make heads or tails of it.

782
00:35:21,205 --> 00:35:22,465
So this guy has to step in and do it, why?

783
00:35:22,465 --> 00:35:24,064
Because I'm not catching a word of it.

784
00:35:24,064 --> 00:35:25,005
[Lost in translation]
He really lays into me hard.

785
00:35:25,005 --> 00:35:26,405
So naturally, this guy gets pissed off, right?

786
00:35:26,405 --> 00:35:28,031
And then he starts cursing me out.

787
00:35:28,031 --> 00:35:30,303
So whatever curse words exist in Italy,

788
00:35:30,303 --> 00:35:32,369
if there are dozens of them out there,

789
00:35:32,369 --> 00:35:35,031
I've heard each one
ten times at the bare minimum.

790
00:35:35,031 --> 00:35:37,072
So you were grinding it out
in a pretty hardcore spot, huh?

791
00:35:37,072 --> 00:35:39,092
- It's Michelin, after all.
- True enough.

792
00:35:39,092 --> 00:35:41,151
The standards are no joke.

793
00:35:41,151 --> 00:35:42,832
But cave to all that?

794
00:35:42,832 --> 00:35:44,436
You won't last.

795
00:35:44,436 --> 00:35:45,734
There's this saying,

796
00:35:45,734 --> 00:35:48,230
no paradise waiting at the place you ran to.

797
00:35:49,136 --> 00:35:50,806
Dropping wisdom now...

798
00:35:50,806 --> 00:35:53,512
Honestly, the workload makes zero sense.

799
00:35:53,512 --> 00:35:55,308
You're pulling 100-hour weeks with no pay,

800
00:35:55,308 --> 00:35:57,711
eating verbal abuse on top of it,

801
00:35:57,711 --> 00:35:59,812
is there really a reason to stick it out?

802
00:36:00,512 --> 00:36:01,503
For me personally,

803
00:36:01,503 --> 00:36:03,283
other people might see it differently,
but for my part,

804
00:36:03,283 --> 00:36:04,984
I'm convinced that those years are the reason

805
00:36:04,984 --> 00:36:08,487
I'm standing where I'm standing today.

806
00:36:10,423 --> 00:36:11,728
[Sniff]

807
00:36:11,728 --> 00:36:12,973
[Baffled]
What's with the solo awe trip...

808
00:36:12,973 --> 00:36:15,993
Nothing about that even calls for awe,
and there he is, moved by himself.

809
00:36:15,993 --> 00:36:17,642
- I'm tearing up.
- Watching this interview,

810
00:36:17,642 --> 00:36:19,332
suddenly my hopes are dropping.

811
00:36:21,052 --> 00:36:21,813
How come?

812
00:36:21,813 --> 00:36:24,053
- My expectations just took a dive...
- He's sabotaging his own thing.

813
00:36:24,053 --> 00:36:25,815
But this honestly feels
like a series finale vibe,

814
00:36:25,815 --> 00:36:27,373
right from the get-go.

815
00:36:27,992 --> 00:36:30,953
Even after those 100-hour weeks,
only the good memories stuck.

816
00:36:30,953 --> 00:36:34,650
Looking back, most things go that way.

817
00:36:34,650 --> 00:36:37,016
[Sung Jun at 25]
Just a cook's posture,

818
00:36:38,353 --> 00:36:40,541
a cook's fire,

819
00:36:41,372 --> 00:36:43,623
[Naples mentor, Chef Nino Di Costanzo]
the mindset side of things,

820
00:36:43,623 --> 00:36:45,452
I picked up the fundamentals there.

821
00:36:45,452 --> 00:36:46,760
How is this so moving?

822
00:36:46,760 --> 00:36:49,896
[Back then, what was rookie Sung Jun's score?]

823
00:36:49,896 --> 00:36:51,497
A 50?

824
00:36:52,609 --> 00:36:55,702
No matter how good you are,
if you can't communicate,

825
00:36:55,702 --> 00:36:57,549
[Deduction: weak language skills]
you're capped at 50.

826
00:36:57,549 --> 00:37:00,670
So among the half-baked, top score, 50.

827
00:37:00,670 --> 00:37:03,777
- Top of the half-baked.
- That's some positive thinking.

828
00:37:03,777 --> 00:37:04,910
[In that case...]

829
00:37:06,546 --> 00:37:08,581
[A perfect rookie minus the Italian]

830
00:37:08,581 --> 00:37:10,651
Man, they shot this beautifully.

831
00:37:11,283 --> 00:37:14,603
[Taking over a local kitchen in five days?]

832
00:37:14,603 --> 00:37:17,793
The hat here is no joke either.

833
00:37:17,793 --> 00:37:19,759
- Over here...
- Hold up.

834
00:37:19,759 --> 00:37:21,336
Isn't that hat way too small?

835
00:37:21,336 --> 00:37:23,387
Wait, did you actually go to China instead?

836
00:37:23,387 --> 00:37:25,987
The hat's tiny, isn't there a bigger one?

837
00:37:25,987 --> 00:37:27,967
[Hat crisis breaks out]
Looks like a pirate hat.

838
00:37:27,967 --> 00:37:29,836
[Groan]

839
00:37:30,536 --> 00:37:32,770
It's seriously...

840
00:37:32,770 --> 00:37:35,809
When it comes to the restaurant
and kitchen F&B business,

841
00:37:35,809 --> 00:37:38,446
I bet whoever planned this
knows nothing about it.

842
00:37:38,446 --> 00:37:40,506
Honestly, this whole setup makes no sense,

843
00:37:40,506 --> 00:37:42,772
makes zero sense,

844
00:37:42,772 --> 00:37:45,518
and five days means
peeling potatoes the whole time.

845
00:37:46,586 --> 00:37:49,562
[5-part series: rookie meets potatoes]

846
00:37:49,562 --> 00:37:51,293
This just turned into Screening Humanity.

847
00:37:51,293 --> 00:37:52,745
[Kwon Sung Jun (11-year chef)]
Today again,

848
00:37:52,745 --> 00:37:55,245
Sung Jun peels nothing but potatoes.

849
00:37:56,602 --> 00:37:58,983
Everyone will see
that this is flat-out impossible.

850
00:37:58,983 --> 00:38:00,762
Flat-out impossible.

851
00:38:00,762 --> 00:38:03,460
But pulling off the impossible,

852
00:38:03,460 --> 00:38:05,432
that's my specialty.

853
00:38:06,130 --> 00:38:09,678
Honestly, I don't think
I need the full five days.

854
00:38:09,678 --> 00:38:12,078
[Rookie to head chef]
Three days should do it.

855
00:38:12,078 --> 00:38:13,003
[Slurp]

856
00:38:13,003 --> 00:38:14,614
[Tsk]

857
00:38:14,614 --> 00:38:17,369
- Sung Jun, really...
- That line is pure Hyun Seok.

858
00:38:17,369 --> 00:38:21,770
Making the crew hiss like that
with one line, that's a talent.

859
00:38:21,770 --> 00:38:23,089
Is that just your nature?

860
00:38:23,089 --> 00:38:24,625
Yeah. What about it?

861
00:38:24,625 --> 00:38:25,985
- News to you?
- Is it weird?

862
00:38:25,985 --> 00:38:27,102
- He's always been this way.
- What?

863
00:38:27,102 --> 00:38:28,528
[Still warming up]
- This is rough. - What's rough about it?

864
00:38:28,528 --> 00:38:30,529
[All sunshine]
Am I the only one out of the loop?

865
00:38:31,397 --> 00:38:35,297
It's easy. Crush whatever they give you,

866
00:38:35,297 --> 00:38:37,203
and they have to promote you.

867
00:38:37,203 --> 00:38:39,809
Say they hand you tiramisu,

868
00:38:39,809 --> 00:38:41,674
walk you through the recipe.

869
00:38:41,674 --> 00:38:43,610
You nail it.

870
00:38:43,610 --> 00:38:45,645
[Dessert station]
Then it's on to pasta.

871
00:38:45,645 --> 00:38:47,236
[Pasta station]

872
00:38:47,236 --> 00:38:48,385
Solid with pasta too?

873
00:38:48,385 --> 00:38:49,864
"All right, try risotto."

874
00:38:49,864 --> 00:38:52,752
Prove you've got it,
and you move up to the next.

875
00:38:52,752 --> 00:38:56,136
Because the kitchen runs on pure merit,

876
00:38:56,136 --> 00:38:57,665
if you can't pull off what they ask?

877
00:38:57,665 --> 00:38:59,559
You stay stuck on that one task.

878
00:38:59,559 --> 00:39:01,194
[Stuck on potato duty]

879
00:39:01,194 --> 00:39:04,063
[Or moving up to the burners]

880
00:39:04,063 --> 00:39:05,698
[So which kind of place this time?]

881
00:39:05,698 --> 00:39:07,169
For me personally,

882
00:39:07,169 --> 00:39:09,503
something on the casual side,

883
00:39:09,503 --> 00:39:12,205
a trattoria, for example.

884
00:39:12,205 --> 00:39:14,114
[Trattoria]

885
00:39:14,114 --> 00:39:15,236
[Traditional home-style fare]

886
00:39:15,236 --> 00:39:18,017
So a trattoria's a traditional home-style spot.

887
00:39:18,017 --> 00:39:20,136
A casual joint, the trattoria.

888
00:39:20,136 --> 00:39:23,496
[Recipes passed down through the family]
Old-school folks doing the cooking.

889
00:39:23,496 --> 00:39:25,817
[Soulful home cooking on the menu]
So kind of like our baekban joints?

890
00:39:25,817 --> 00:39:26,903
Pretty much.

891
00:39:26,903 --> 00:39:29,176
[Italy's cozy neighborhood baekban spot]
So that's a trattoria.

892
00:39:29,176 --> 00:39:32,057
Working a place like that, that'd be amazing.

893
00:39:32,057 --> 00:39:34,594
[Trattoria trait 1]
Tiny little neighborhood restaurants,

894
00:39:34,594 --> 00:39:37,202
[Mostly local regulars]
only locals walk in.

895
00:39:37,202 --> 00:39:39,131
In Italy especially,

896
00:39:39,131 --> 00:39:42,336
tasting great matters, sure,

897
00:39:42,336 --> 00:39:45,069
but the real test is how you take
the best from your own region,

898
00:39:45,069 --> 00:39:47,212
use it right, and honor tradition.

899
00:39:47,212 --> 00:39:49,132
Italy definitely has that going on,

900
00:39:49,132 --> 00:39:53,102
this rule about honoring
tradition through local food,

901
00:39:53,102 --> 00:39:55,281
that's Italy's signature.

902
00:39:55,281 --> 00:39:57,469
[Trattoria potato pasta, meanwhile]

903
00:39:57,469 --> 00:39:59,451
Potato pasta?

904
00:39:59,451 --> 00:40:00,553
- Unusual, huh?
- That is unusual.

905
00:40:00,553 --> 00:40:03,069
[Traditional recipes packed with soul]
Authentic Naples pasta.

906
00:40:03,069 --> 00:40:05,825
[Rustic, warm comfort food]
Potato pasta, first I'm hearing of it.

907
00:40:07,327 --> 00:40:09,829
[In a Naples tradition master's kitchen]

908
00:40:09,829 --> 00:40:12,932
[Matfia's about to show his stuff]

909
00:40:12,932 --> 00:40:16,536
So will your cooking actually fly over there?

910
00:40:16,536 --> 00:40:18,237
Over there?

911
00:40:18,237 --> 00:40:20,974
It'll crush it worldwide, not just there.

912
00:40:20,974 --> 00:40:23,309
What do you mean over there? The whole world.

913
00:40:23,309 --> 00:40:24,444
[Cocky Mode Activated]

914
00:40:24,444 --> 00:40:26,012
That's right.

915
00:40:26,012 --> 00:40:28,114
- Isn't that obvious?
- Whoa, this seat...

916
00:40:28,114 --> 00:40:31,750
[From Sam]
Let's invite Chef Choi Hyun Seok here.

917
00:40:32,719 --> 00:40:34,220
Fact.

918
00:40:39,926 --> 00:40:40,893
[So how do you plan to hide your identity?]

919
00:40:40,893 --> 00:40:43,029
Been thinking about it.

920
00:40:43,029 --> 00:40:44,763
Celebrity won't work.

921
00:40:45,698 --> 00:40:47,967
[They might not buy it]
What's that? What's with the photo?

922
00:40:47,967 --> 00:40:49,068
Singer is out too.

923
00:40:49,068 --> 00:40:50,970
Singer won't fly.

924
00:40:50,970 --> 00:40:53,940
Wait, I really tried everything.

925
00:40:53,940 --> 00:40:55,942
[Vocal skills issue]
All within just a year.

926
00:40:55,942 --> 00:40:59,412
[What should it be?]

927
00:40:59,412 --> 00:41:01,514
How about an athlete?

928
00:41:01,514 --> 00:41:03,716
- People always tell me...
- Right, athlete suits you well.

929
00:41:03,716 --> 00:41:06,252
They say I look like a baseball player.

930
00:41:06,252 --> 00:41:08,287
Honestly I love baseball.

931
00:41:08,287 --> 00:41:09,922
[Sung Jun's baseball history (legit)]
Joined baseball clubs and stuff.

932
00:41:09,922 --> 00:41:12,258
Played on the school team too.

933
00:41:12,258 --> 00:41:14,827
Truly into it and quite knowledgeable.

934
00:41:14,827 --> 00:41:17,963
Going with the baseball player angle.

935
00:41:18,698 --> 00:41:19,899
Let's make it an infielder.

936
00:41:19,899 --> 00:41:21,968
- My build isn't a pitcher's build.
- What's with that picture?

937
00:41:21,968 --> 00:41:25,571
Quit after high school due to injury.

938
00:41:25,571 --> 00:41:26,572
Something like that?

939
00:41:26,572 --> 00:41:29,509
[Backstory done in seconds]

940
00:41:29,509 --> 00:41:32,078
[Resume]
[Name, Address, Contact]

941
00:41:32,078 --> 00:41:36,050
His face changes so much across one screen.

942
00:41:36,050 --> 00:41:38,051
Tons of reference photos
because we shot so many.

943
00:41:38,051 --> 00:41:39,352
Honestly I thought it was
Chef Jung Ho Young at first.

944
00:41:39,352 --> 00:41:40,953
- Why are there so many?
- It keeps switching.

945
00:41:40,953 --> 00:41:43,423
Swear it looked like
Chef Jung Ho Young at a glance.

946
00:41:43,423 --> 00:41:45,324
Listen up, the name matters.

947
00:41:45,324 --> 00:41:47,159
So what name will you go by?

948
00:41:48,594 --> 00:41:50,730
Should pick an Italian name!

949
00:41:50,730 --> 00:41:52,765
Something like Andrea.

950
00:41:52,765 --> 00:41:55,568
Or Alberto, these are super common.

951
00:41:55,568 --> 00:41:57,437
Why not Elio?

952
00:41:57,437 --> 00:41:59,272
[Sung Jun's Italian name]
Nobody really uses this one.

953
00:41:59,272 --> 00:42:01,174
So probably only me.

954
00:42:01,174 --> 00:42:03,676
Search for Elio and it'll pop up.

955
00:42:03,676 --> 00:42:04,701
Yeah.

956
00:42:04,701 --> 00:42:06,372
[High risk of getting caught via search]

957
00:42:10,283 --> 00:42:12,518
Or maybe just go with Sam.

958
00:42:13,653 --> 00:42:15,455
Picking a name? Easy!

959
00:42:15,455 --> 00:42:17,790
[To Chef Sam: Thanks for the name...
from Sam Kwon]

960
00:42:17,790 --> 00:42:19,592
So...

961
00:42:19,592 --> 00:42:21,894
- Sam it is.
- Seriously?

962
00:42:21,894 --> 00:42:23,830
- Wait, for real?
- Dead serious.

963
00:42:23,830 --> 00:42:25,531
- So, you went by Sam Kwon?
- Sam Kwon.

964
00:42:25,531 --> 00:42:26,999
- Yeah.
- That's hilarious.

965
00:42:26,999 --> 00:42:28,600
Let's just roll with Sam Kwon.

966
00:42:28,600 --> 00:42:29,936
[What made you want to be a kitchen rookie?]

967
00:42:29,936 --> 00:42:32,205
All these years of cooking,

968
00:42:32,205 --> 00:42:34,607
I became a boss pretty early on.

969
00:42:34,607 --> 00:42:36,509
I was the boss at 27, so...

970
00:42:36,509 --> 00:42:38,211
The rookie life

971
00:42:38,211 --> 00:42:41,769
only lasted a year or two
before I jumped straight to being a boss.

972
00:42:42,515 --> 00:42:45,685
As a rookie, as part of the kitchen,

973
00:42:45,685 --> 00:42:47,353
not as the boss,

974
00:42:47,353 --> 00:42:49,989
I really want to get back to who I used to be.

975
00:42:49,989 --> 00:42:51,657
That feeling was pretty big, I think.

976
00:42:52,357 --> 00:42:55,570
That pure feeling,
when I first started cooking,

977
00:42:55,570 --> 00:42:58,097
- I want to feel it again.
- Finding the first spark.

978
00:42:58,865 --> 00:43:00,566
My motto.

979
00:43:00,566 --> 00:43:02,602
Mai Paura.

980
00:43:02,602 --> 00:43:05,204
There's a saying in Italy, "Mai Paura."

981
00:43:05,204 --> 00:43:06,706
Don't be scared.

982
00:43:06,706 --> 00:43:08,608
It means "No fear."

983
00:43:08,608 --> 00:43:11,184
Italians say it all the time.

984
00:43:11,184 --> 00:43:14,847
I picked up that mindset from them,
and I live by it!

985
00:43:14,847 --> 00:43:16,943
Living that way is
why things worked out, I think.

986
00:43:16,943 --> 00:43:19,870
[With all of Sung Jun's resolve poured in]

987
00:43:22,288 --> 00:43:24,223
[A resume packed to the brim]
Oh, look at that.

988
00:43:24,223 --> 00:43:25,397
A whole resume, huh?

989
00:43:25,397 --> 00:43:27,627
Yeah, wrote it up. Put real work into it.

990
00:43:27,627 --> 00:43:30,430
[Carrying fierce resolve across the continent]

991
00:43:32,404 --> 00:43:35,000
Whoa, that's how it goes?

992
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:36,921
[Naples, Italy]
Off it flies.

993
00:43:38,548 --> 00:43:40,439
Outskirts and still packed.

994
00:43:40,439 --> 00:43:42,069
Naples is really...

995
00:43:42,069 --> 00:43:44,210
- Dense with people.
- I'll bet.

996
00:43:44,210 --> 00:43:45,993
Hi there!

997
00:43:47,380 --> 00:43:48,814
[Warm smile]
Who's that?

998
00:43:48,814 --> 00:43:50,249
[These two look-alikes are]
Yes, yes.

999
00:43:50,249 --> 00:43:52,851
- Such warm faces.
- Yeah, really.

1000
00:43:52,851 --> 00:43:55,555
[the new rookie Sam Kwon's bosses]
Oh, she's the chef? The owner chef.

1001
00:43:55,555 --> 00:43:57,690
- Hi, I'm Luisa.
- They're sisters.

1002
00:43:57,690 --> 00:43:59,759
Hi, I'm Laura.

1003
00:43:59,759 --> 00:44:04,197
This place is run by our family.

1004
00:44:04,197 --> 00:44:06,599
We've kept the shop going
right here for three generations.

1005
00:44:06,599 --> 00:44:07,934
- Three generations.
- Three whole generations?

1006
00:44:07,934 --> 00:44:09,101
It's been around forever.

1007
00:44:09,101 --> 00:44:13,839
After our grandparents opened the place...

1008
00:44:13,839 --> 00:44:16,488
- So it started right after World War Two.
- Exactly.

1009
00:44:16,488 --> 00:44:17,368
Then in the 90s,

1010
00:44:17,368 --> 00:44:20,736
- the two of us sisters took over.
- Such young days.

1011
00:44:21,347 --> 00:44:23,049
[The sister chefs' traditional touch,
passed down through the family]

1012
00:44:23,049 --> 00:44:25,251
I don't even have to see the food here.

1013
00:44:25,251 --> 00:44:26,619
- Looks delicious already.
- It is.

1014
00:44:26,619 --> 00:44:27,853
[The charm that's kept
the neighborhood regulars hooked for years]

1015
00:44:27,853 --> 00:44:30,122
I genuinely wanted
to work at a place like that.

1016
00:44:31,657 --> 00:44:34,627
- Hello, good evening.
- Hello. Hello, princess.

1017
00:44:34,627 --> 00:44:36,429
[Welcoming regulars like family every time]
You are so pretty.

1018
00:44:36,429 --> 00:44:37,930
- Buon lavoro.
- Have a good work.

1019
00:44:37,930 --> 00:44:39,498
- Grazie.
- See you later.

1020
00:44:40,099 --> 00:44:41,500
[A humble neighborhood spot
on the edge of Naples]

1021
00:44:41,500 --> 00:44:44,136
- They picked an amazing restaurant.
- The food looks delicious.

1022
00:44:44,136 --> 00:44:45,825
The food was great,
the whole place was wonderful.

1023
00:44:45,825 --> 00:44:48,207
[Word spread about the sisters'
incredible cooking]

1024
00:44:48,207 --> 00:44:51,344
[Laura, Luisa]
[Featured in cookbooks]

1025
00:44:51,344 --> 00:44:53,813
[Listed multiple times in Trattoria food guide]

1026
00:44:53,813 --> 00:44:55,348
So Naples actually,

1027
00:44:55,348 --> 00:44:57,016
right after World War Two, was completely...

1028
00:44:57,016 --> 00:44:58,417
- a devastated neighborhood.
- Just unbelievably rough.

1029
00:44:58,417 --> 00:45:00,353
- If this home cooking started back then...
- Yeah.

1030
00:45:00,353 --> 00:45:01,988
Honestly when you really think about it,

1031
00:45:01,988 --> 00:45:04,056
the food and everything else,

1032
00:45:04,056 --> 00:45:05,324
it's really, how do I put this,

1033
00:45:05,324 --> 00:45:06,559
so deeply rooted in the land.

1034
00:45:06,559 --> 00:45:08,394
Yeah, exactly.

1035
00:45:08,394 --> 00:45:13,575
["When you have nothing,
anything becomes an ingredient."]

1036
00:45:14,467 --> 00:45:18,304
[A resume from a new kitchen rookie
has arrived]

1037
00:45:18,304 --> 00:45:21,240
[at the sisters' restaurant,
the very history of Naples cuisine]

1038
00:45:21,240 --> 00:45:23,476
- Okay.
- Okay.

1039
00:45:23,476 --> 00:45:25,077
It looks good.

1040
00:45:25,077 --> 00:45:27,179
Oh, this is how they did it.

1041
00:45:27,179 --> 00:45:29,615
He prepared this really well.

1042
00:45:29,615 --> 00:45:30,750
Take a look.

1043
00:45:30,750 --> 00:45:33,586
I'm going to need my glasses.

1044
00:45:33,586 --> 00:45:34,687
This is a resume?

1045
00:45:34,687 --> 00:45:36,322
Yeah, it's a resume.

1046
00:45:36,322 --> 00:45:38,090
Sam Kwah.

1047
00:45:38,090 --> 00:45:39,158
Sam Kwah.

1048
00:45:39,158 --> 00:45:40,493
[Oh, so you're Sam Kwah]
Sam Kwah.

1049
00:45:40,493 --> 00:45:41,627
Tricky to pronounce.

1050
00:45:41,627 --> 00:45:43,329
- Honestly the sound "Kwon"
- "Kwon" is tough.

1051
00:45:43,329 --> 00:45:44,630
It really is hard.

1052
00:45:44,630 --> 00:45:50,369
I played baseball up until I was 20.

1053
00:45:50,369 --> 00:45:55,441
I had no choice but to quit baseball,

1054
00:45:55,441 --> 00:45:59,063
but sports built my discipline

1055
00:45:59,063 --> 00:46:01,013
- Right.
- and sense of responsibility.

1056
00:46:01,013 --> 00:46:05,584
And I also learned how crucial teamwork is.

1057
00:46:05,584 --> 00:46:07,953
Teamwork matters, no doubt.

1058
00:46:07,953 --> 00:46:09,622
If you give me a chance,

1059
00:46:09,622 --> 00:46:13,259
I'll learn with all my heart
and work my hardest.

1060
00:46:13,259 --> 00:46:15,328
Thank you.

1061
00:46:15,328 --> 00:46:17,463
[The sister bosses think
this is just a documentary shoot]

1062
00:46:17,463 --> 00:46:19,332
Looking at what's in the resume...

1063
00:46:19,332 --> 00:46:20,273
Okay.

1064
00:46:20,273 --> 00:46:21,367
[Laura's first impression of Sam Kwah is...]

1065
00:46:21,367 --> 00:46:23,903
Looking at what's in the resume...

1066
00:46:23,903 --> 00:46:25,840
[How does baseball player
"Sam Kwah" come across?]

1067
00:46:25,840 --> 00:46:30,371
His first impression is really great!

1068
00:46:31,177 --> 00:46:32,812
[Jealous]
She liked him.

1069
00:46:32,812 --> 00:46:34,613
[Knew I could count on my bosses]
Knew it.

1070
00:46:34,613 --> 00:46:37,628
And he looks really decisive.

1071
00:46:37,628 --> 00:46:38,784
[Looks decisive?]

1072
00:46:38,784 --> 00:46:40,319
- The AI really...
- That suits him though.

1073
00:46:40,319 --> 00:46:41,454
So much.

1074
00:46:41,454 --> 00:46:43,422
[Hesitating]

1075
00:46:43,422 --> 00:46:46,692
But he probably has no clue
what he's about to walk into.

1076
00:46:46,692 --> 00:46:48,060
Right?

1077
00:46:48,060 --> 00:46:52,031
If you've never worked in a kitchen,
you can only imagine,

1078
00:46:52,031 --> 00:46:56,936
but living it firsthand is
a whole different beast.

1079
00:46:56,936 --> 00:47:00,206
He's about to feel like
he's in a massive whirlwind.

1080
00:47:00,206 --> 00:47:02,775
He's got a mountain of stuff to learn.

1081
00:47:02,775 --> 00:47:04,210
The kitchen isn't easy.

1082
00:47:04,210 --> 00:47:07,346
- But they have such a warm face.
- They really do.

1083
00:47:07,346 --> 00:47:10,416
[What kind of place is
Sam Kwon's Naples workplace?]

1084
00:47:10,416 --> 00:47:13,386
We'll see if that kid has what it takes.

1085
00:47:15,254 --> 00:47:17,329
If I don't see those qualities...

1086
00:47:20,659 --> 00:47:22,361
No.

1087
00:47:22,361 --> 00:47:23,662
I don't waste time on people like that.

1088
00:47:23,662 --> 00:47:25,064
She seems like a different person.

1089
00:47:25,064 --> 00:47:26,198
Work mode is something else.

1090
00:47:26,198 --> 00:47:28,000
Whoa, that's a lot of people.

1091
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:29,769
Her expression really shifted.

1092
00:47:29,769 --> 00:47:31,137
In the kitchen, definitely.

1093
00:47:31,137 --> 00:47:34,907
[The rookie spot he's returning to]

1094
00:47:34,907 --> 00:47:37,998
[might be tougher than expected...]

1095
00:47:39,178 --> 00:47:40,813
[A no-nonsense kitchen vibe
is sweeping through Naples]

1096
00:47:40,813 --> 00:47:43,044
The vibe is completely different.

1097
00:47:44,383 --> 00:47:48,888
[Meanwhile, Sung Jun]

1098
00:47:48,888 --> 00:47:50,389
Hello.

1099
00:47:50,389 --> 00:47:53,292
It's been a while since I last used Italian.

1100
00:47:53,292 --> 00:47:55,961
So I've been watching Italian cooking shows

1101
00:47:55,961 --> 00:47:59,131
to get my feel back.

1102
00:47:59,999 --> 00:48:02,851
[A study method fit
for the survival show authority...]

1103
00:48:02,851 --> 00:48:04,283
But why the mask?

1104
00:48:04,283 --> 00:48:05,905
[Star chef]
Worried people will recognize you?

1105
00:48:05,905 --> 00:48:07,840
[Unexpected jab]

1106
00:48:07,840 --> 00:48:11,010
Should've just gone
with a celebrity for your job.

1107
00:48:11,010 --> 00:48:12,211
So I can't wear a mask?

1108
00:48:12,211 --> 00:48:13,813
[Kwon Sung Jun,
the chef who wants to be a star]

1109
00:48:13,813 --> 00:48:16,248
[Here's the thing though...]
<i>I don't need a strategy.</i>

1110
00:48:16,248 --> 00:48:18,184
<i>Just nail it.</i>

1111
00:48:18,184 --> 00:48:22,092
[Said he didn't need strategy...
but studying like crazy]

1112
00:48:22,913 --> 00:48:24,056
[Even cramming Punic War history?]

1113
00:48:24,056 --> 00:48:26,158
- Even history?
- Oh, history?

1114
00:48:26,158 --> 00:48:28,227
This is really important, everyone.

1115
00:48:28,227 --> 00:48:32,631
[After 14 hours of history & language cram...]
Honestly, learning any country's food

1116
00:48:32,631 --> 00:48:34,803
- means history is a must.
- Right, that's where it has to start.

1117
00:48:34,803 --> 00:48:36,769
His approach is different from mine.

1118
00:48:36,769 --> 00:48:38,337
I want to play...

1119
00:48:39,038 --> 00:48:40,941
Naples after such a long time...

1120
00:48:41,574 --> 00:48:42,766
Hold on, is this the right place?

1121
00:48:42,766 --> 00:48:44,762
[Pushing past the longing,
heading to the lodging first]

1122
00:48:48,981 --> 00:48:51,083
- Oh, it's a duplex?
- Yeah.

1123
00:48:51,083 --> 00:48:52,551
The place was nice.

1124
00:48:52,551 --> 00:48:53,913
[Fumbling...]

1125
00:48:55,521 --> 00:48:57,590
The room was a little weird.

1126
00:48:57,590 --> 00:48:58,657
He said it was weird.

1127
00:48:58,657 --> 00:49:00,960
[Naples club opening?]
Whoa, why are the lights doing that?

1128
00:49:00,960 --> 00:49:03,362
- Naples style.
- Oh really?

1129
00:49:03,362 --> 00:49:04,997
- Isn't this a club?
- It's not.

1130
00:49:04,997 --> 00:49:06,799
Why would a home need lights like this?

1131
00:49:06,799 --> 00:49:07,967
Exactly.

1132
00:49:07,967 --> 00:49:09,534
I was thrown off.

1133
00:49:10,336 --> 00:49:13,591
[After the somewhat intense check-in ceremony]

1134
00:49:13,591 --> 00:49:14,573
[Thankfully the kitchen lights are tame]

1135
00:49:14,573 --> 00:49:17,053
- It's clean.
- Real clean. It was nice.

1136
00:49:17,053 --> 00:49:19,831
[True to chef form, scanning the kitchen first]

1137
00:49:20,813 --> 00:49:24,116
[Out of habit, checking the fridge too]

1138
00:49:24,116 --> 00:49:26,552
- Same layout as a Korean studio.
- Yeah.

1139
00:49:26,552 --> 00:49:29,054
[Focused]
[Room tour wrapped in a minute]

1140
00:49:29,054 --> 00:49:30,489
[Room tour done in a breeze,
glued to his phone instead]

1141
00:49:30,489 --> 00:49:32,491
What's he watching so intently on his phone?

1142
00:49:32,491 --> 00:49:34,026
[What is he doing?]
Right?

1143
00:49:34,727 --> 00:49:37,200
[Oh, look at the time...]

1144
00:49:37,200 --> 00:49:38,209
[Current time: 11:15 PM]

1145
00:49:38,209 --> 00:49:40,333
[Late into the night,
finally getting ready to wash up and sleep...]

1146
00:49:40,333 --> 00:49:43,434
[Water rushing]

1147
00:50:00,837 --> 00:50:03,937
[A doorbell at this hour?
Rushing out mid-shower...]

1148
00:50:03,937 --> 00:50:06,070
[Leaving the door wide open, where to?]

1149
00:50:06,070 --> 00:50:07,604
Thanks.

1150
00:50:07,970 --> 00:50:11,037
[He returns
with a mysterious armful of something...]

1151
00:50:11,037 --> 00:50:12,970
[A burger to mark his first night in Naples]
They have delivery here?

1152
00:50:12,970 --> 00:50:14,988
- Of course.
- Italy does delivery?

1153
00:50:14,988 --> 00:50:17,174
- They have delivery in Italy?
- Absolutely.

1154
00:50:17,174 --> 00:50:19,209
- They really do it a lot.
- Of course they do.

1155
00:50:19,209 --> 00:50:20,903
I was hungry.

1156
00:50:20,903 --> 00:50:22,046
[Chomp]

1157
00:50:22,046 --> 00:50:23,514
While watching a video.

1158
00:50:23,514 --> 00:50:25,081
[Late-night snack with Italian TV]
MasterChef.

1159
00:50:25,081 --> 00:50:26,617
Once I got to Naples,

1160
00:50:26,617 --> 00:50:28,485
I'm Italian from here on out.

1161
00:50:28,485 --> 00:50:30,621
Only Italian songs, only Italian movies,

1162
00:50:30,621 --> 00:50:31,855
only Italian dramas.

1163
00:50:31,855 --> 00:50:34,692
Without that, adapting takes way too long.

1164
00:50:34,692 --> 00:50:36,660
I am Italian.

1165
00:50:36,660 --> 00:50:38,128
[Filling up on mental fuel]
[Eyes locked in]

1166
00:50:38,128 --> 00:50:40,931
You have to keep listening to use the language.

1167
00:50:40,931 --> 00:50:43,567
The settings in your head have to switch.

1168
00:50:43,567 --> 00:50:45,903
[Determined]
Putting in the work.

1169
00:50:45,903 --> 00:50:48,472
- What?
- How long did you actually live in Naples?

1170
00:50:48,472 --> 00:50:50,374
Me? Alright, let's roll the footage.

1171
00:50:50,374 --> 00:50:52,643
Tell us how long you lived there.
Come on, spill it.

1172
00:50:52,643 --> 00:50:53,944
- Bet folks are dying to know.
- Come on, spill it.

1173
00:50:53,944 --> 00:50:55,579
- Quick.
- You've got to tell us.

1174
00:50:55,579 --> 00:50:56,780
- How long did you live there?
- In Naples?

1175
00:50:56,780 --> 00:50:58,482
Just under a year, maybe.

1176
00:50:58,482 --> 00:50:59,883
- Under a year?
- Exactly how many months?

1177
00:50:59,883 --> 00:51:01,118
[Wailing]
Exact numbers feel a bit much.

1178
00:51:01,118 --> 00:51:02,319
Exactly how many months?

1179
00:51:02,319 --> 00:51:04,855
- See, the thing is... I...
- Nine months, right?

1180
00:51:04,855 --> 00:51:06,156
I head to Italy every year now, see.

1181
00:51:06,156 --> 00:51:07,891
- Nine months means...
- I thought it was four or five years.

1182
00:51:07,891 --> 00:51:09,393
So nine months is, like,

1183
00:51:09,393 --> 00:51:12,423
less than the time I've spent there.

1184
00:51:12,423 --> 00:51:15,393
- Way less than your time there.
- Let's roll.

1185
00:51:17,101 --> 00:51:18,769
- Time for bed?
- Bed it is.

1186
00:51:18,769 --> 00:51:20,738
- One ten in the morning.
- After the burger.

1187
00:51:20,738 --> 00:51:21,872
- Straight.
- Straight to it.

1188
00:51:21,872 --> 00:51:23,674
- Out like a light.
- Riding the sugar spike.

1189
00:51:23,674 --> 00:51:25,842
[8h 50m till work, sugar-fueled sleep attempt]

1190
00:51:32,922 --> 00:51:35,519
- Naples is just the best, seriously.
- So gorgeous.

1191
00:51:35,519 --> 00:51:37,820
[Buongiorno!]

1192
00:51:40,024 --> 00:51:41,158
[Sam Kwon's First Day on the Job]
- Sam Kwon. - Sam Kwon.

1193
00:51:41,158 --> 00:51:42,658
Sam Kwon.

1194
00:51:44,728 --> 00:51:47,006
[Wiggle]

1195
00:51:48,832 --> 00:51:50,134
[Snap]

1196
00:51:50,134 --> 00:51:52,002
Looks like he slept like a rock.

1197
00:51:52,002 --> 00:51:53,771
- I passed out after the burger.
- Crashed right after eating.

1198
00:51:53,771 --> 00:51:54,905
[Puffy]
Straight to sleep.

1199
00:51:54,905 --> 00:51:56,740
[Naples burger]
His face turned into a burger.

1200
00:51:56,740 --> 00:51:58,275
Look how puffy my face is.

1201
00:51:58,275 --> 00:51:59,810
[What time is it?]

1202
00:51:59,810 --> 00:52:01,278
[7:45 AM]

1203
00:52:01,278 --> 00:52:04,701
[1h 15m before day one starts]

1204
00:52:05,649 --> 00:52:08,520
[Starts at nine... still got time...]

1205
00:52:09,653 --> 00:52:14,495
[First, folding the blanket neatly]

1206
00:52:18,962 --> 00:52:22,232
[Checking out the terrace, dark last night]

1207
00:52:22,232 --> 00:52:23,367
- There's a terrace right out front.
- There's a terrace too.

1208
00:52:23,367 --> 00:52:25,369
There's a terrace like this?

1209
00:52:25,369 --> 00:52:26,870
[Breathing in the Naples morning air]

1210
00:52:26,870 --> 00:52:30,188
[A quick morning stretch]

1211
00:52:32,275 --> 00:52:33,444
[#FirstDayLetsGo]
Is that a lemon?

1212
00:52:33,444 --> 00:52:35,179
Lemons are famous in Naples,

1213
00:52:35,179 --> 00:52:36,480
so plenty of homes grow them.

1214
00:52:36,480 --> 00:52:37,948
- Lemons rule the south.
- Yeah.

1215
00:52:37,948 --> 00:52:39,583
[Mediterranean climate
fills every block with lemons]

1216
00:52:39,583 --> 00:52:40,984
[Italian News ON]

1217
00:52:40,984 --> 00:52:42,119
[Mind training rolls into the morning]

1218
00:52:42,119 --> 00:52:44,054
<i>I am Italian.</i>

1219
00:52:44,054 --> 00:52:45,522
News right from morning.

1220
00:52:45,522 --> 00:52:46,490
[Trickle]

1221
00:52:46,490 --> 00:52:49,675
- A cup of coffee.
- He's turning local at warp speed.

1222
00:52:49,675 --> 00:52:50,928
<i>I am Italian.</i>

1223
00:52:50,928 --> 00:52:52,170
[A morning espresso, true to an Italian]

1224
00:52:52,170 --> 00:52:54,870
[Knocked it back in two sips, heading out]

1225
00:52:55,537 --> 00:52:58,304
[Slapping on the cap for the Sam Kwon disguise]

1226
00:52:58,304 --> 00:53:01,038
[One last look-check before day one]

1227
00:53:01,038 --> 00:53:02,339
<i>Mai Paura.</i>

1228
00:53:02,339 --> 00:53:03,440
Don't be scared.

1229
00:53:03,440 --> 00:53:04,770
[One final mantra to anchor himself]

1230
00:53:06,970 --> 00:53:11,749
[Deep breath out, off to work!]

1231
00:53:11,749 --> 00:53:12,983
[8:15 AM]

1232
00:53:12,983 --> 00:53:16,037
[45 minutes before day one]

1233
00:53:18,549 --> 00:53:20,958
- No nerves at all.
- Such fresh air.

1234
00:53:20,958 --> 00:53:22,104
Honestly, I wasn't nervous.

1235
00:53:22,104 --> 00:53:24,094
But look how blue that sky is,

1236
00:53:24,094 --> 00:53:25,595
right?

1237
00:53:26,396 --> 00:53:28,665
The sky in Italy is genuinely blue.

1238
00:53:28,665 --> 00:53:30,634
[And the people who match that weather]

1239
00:53:30,634 --> 00:53:32,169
Hello.

1240
00:53:32,169 --> 00:53:34,403
It's got real charm!

1241
00:53:34,403 --> 00:53:35,739
A little chaotic.

1242
00:53:35,739 --> 00:53:36,940
[Chaotic but free-spirited]

1243
00:53:36,940 --> 00:53:40,110
With a vibe like this, you'd expect
folks to be rough around the edges,

1244
00:53:40,110 --> 00:53:41,445
but they're actually super sweet.

1245
00:53:41,445 --> 00:53:43,812
[Rough on the surface, warm at heart]

1246
00:53:45,682 --> 00:53:47,182
Cute.

1247
00:53:48,752 --> 00:53:50,788
I want to live like that too.

1248
00:53:50,788 --> 00:53:54,237
[Still got to clock in though]

1249
00:53:54,237 --> 00:53:55,759
[But...]

1250
00:53:55,759 --> 00:53:58,154
Pizza smell already this morning?

1251
00:53:58,996 --> 00:54:01,933
[Pizza scent tempts him on the commute]
Naples is the pizza city.

1252
00:54:04,067 --> 00:54:06,231
I'm having that pizza later.

1253
00:54:07,871 --> 00:54:10,541
That cafe is packed, easy to see.

1254
00:54:10,541 --> 00:54:13,677
[His eyes say one cup of coffee can't hurt]
- A cafe? - He's so relaxed.

1255
00:54:13,677 --> 00:54:15,579
Buongiorno.

1256
00:54:15,579 --> 00:54:18,282
One cappuccino, please.

1257
00:54:18,282 --> 00:54:19,883
What's your name?

1258
00:54:19,883 --> 00:54:20,818
It's Sam.

1259
00:54:20,818 --> 00:54:22,786
Sam. I'm Giovanni.

1260
00:54:22,786 --> 00:54:24,814
Giovanni, nice to meet you.

1261
00:54:25,489 --> 00:54:27,157
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

1262
00:54:27,157 --> 00:54:28,704
[Second coffee of the day at 8:30 AM]

1263
00:54:30,194 --> 00:54:31,628
Delicious.

1264
00:54:31,628 --> 00:54:33,831
[Come back, Sam]
Bye. Thank you.

1265
00:54:33,831 --> 00:54:37,134
[Pleasant morning chat with a new friend]
You even had a morning small talk like that.

1266
00:54:37,134 --> 00:54:40,451
[Day one, but happy so far]

1267
00:54:42,372 --> 00:54:44,508
What, it's already fifty... almost fifty past.

1268
00:54:44,508 --> 00:54:45,542
[10 min before day one, 8:50 AM]

1269
00:54:45,542 --> 00:54:47,311
[Flustered]

1270
00:54:47,311 --> 00:54:49,413
Did I take it too easy?

1271
00:54:49,413 --> 00:54:51,681
[A little spooked]
Right?

1272
00:54:52,282 --> 00:54:53,550
But here's the thing...

1273
00:54:53,550 --> 00:54:55,953
Especially when I worked in fine dining,

1274
00:54:55,953 --> 00:54:59,756
showing up less than an hour early
got you scolded.

1275
00:54:59,756 --> 00:55:02,759
So for a nine o'clock shift,
I'd be there by eight.

1276
00:55:02,759 --> 00:55:04,761
I don't know the vibe here yet,

1277
00:55:04,761 --> 00:55:06,563
so showing up too early might rub them wrong.

1278
00:55:06,563 --> 00:55:08,368
It's not exactly good manners.

1279
00:55:08,368 --> 00:55:11,401
[A long-winded resolve to clock in on time]
So I'll just aim to show up right on time.

1280
00:55:11,401 --> 00:55:13,203
It's not that I'm lazy.

1281
00:55:13,904 --> 00:55:17,209
But now that I'm ten minutes out...

1282
00:55:17,908 --> 00:55:19,476
[Really spooked]
Seriously...

1283
00:55:20,077 --> 00:55:21,211
But what did I say?

1284
00:55:21,211 --> 00:55:22,846
Mai Paura.

1285
00:55:22,846 --> 00:55:24,380
Don't be scared.

1286
00:55:24,380 --> 00:55:26,318
So I can survive this.

1287
00:55:27,467 --> 00:55:29,486
[Stunned]
Day one, you'd expect nerves,

1288
00:55:29,486 --> 00:55:31,088
- but no nerves at all.
- Ten minutes till work.

1289
00:55:31,088 --> 00:55:32,356
Chef Jung Ji Sun

1290
00:55:32,356 --> 00:55:33,891
[Everything about the MZ rookie is fresh]
is amazed by every little thing right now.

1291
00:55:33,891 --> 00:55:35,893
Every single move surprises her.

1292
00:55:35,893 --> 00:55:37,027
[Can't look away from Sung Jun...]
MZ style.

1293
00:55:37,027 --> 00:55:38,632
This is MZ right here.

1294
00:55:40,731 --> 00:55:43,775
[Final touch-up while steadying himself]

1295
00:55:44,601 --> 00:55:48,739
[Back to rookie life, nerves rushing in]

1296
00:55:48,739 --> 00:55:50,007
I'll give it my all.

1297
00:55:50,007 --> 00:55:52,109
That's all I've got.

1298
00:55:52,109 --> 00:55:54,912
Stay sharp every moment,

1299
00:55:54,912 --> 00:55:56,813
work with full focus.

1300
00:55:57,514 --> 00:55:59,383
[Walking to steady his nerves, and then...]

1301
00:55:59,383 --> 00:56:01,060
[Stopped]

1302
00:56:02,619 --> 00:56:04,187
Finally arrived.

1303
00:56:04,187 --> 00:56:05,722
Oh, here.

1304
00:56:05,722 --> 00:56:09,126
- So pretty.
- The top is shaped like a dome.

1305
00:56:09,126 --> 00:56:11,728
[Sam Kwon's rookie life unfolds right here]
This is it, right?

1306
00:56:11,728 --> 00:56:13,230
[But the iron door is still firmly shut...]

1307
00:56:13,230 --> 00:56:14,264
Has nobody come in yet?

1308
00:56:14,264 --> 00:56:16,033
Wasn't the start time already past?

1309
00:56:22,108 --> 00:56:24,774
Excuse me.

1310
00:56:25,208 --> 00:56:29,252
[Afraid of being late, he strides in first]

1311
00:56:31,100 --> 00:56:33,081
[Oh right, closing the door behind him...]

1312
00:56:36,108 --> 00:56:37,910
[Knock]

1313
00:56:37,910 --> 00:56:39,540
[Knock]

1314
00:56:39,540 --> 00:56:41,208
Excuse me.

1315
00:56:42,807 --> 00:56:45,546
[Only silence fills the restaurant]

1316
00:56:45,546 --> 00:56:47,115
Nobody around to show me the way.

1317
00:56:47,115 --> 00:56:48,983
So has nobody come in yet?

1318
00:56:48,983 --> 00:56:50,418
If they did, then where is everyone?

1319
00:56:50,418 --> 00:56:51,592
[Peeking into the kitchen too]

1320
00:56:51,592 --> 00:56:53,454
Did I come too early?

1321
00:56:53,454 --> 00:56:55,790
[Around the time everyone should clock in...]
No staff, nobody at all.

1322
00:56:55,790 --> 00:56:57,717
Is everyone here MZ style too?

1323
00:56:57,717 --> 00:57:00,906
[Clueless MZ Sam Kwon pacing the entrance]
Do they walk in right when nine hits?

1324
00:57:00,906 --> 00:57:03,294
[Just then]

1325
00:57:04,198 --> 00:57:07,568
[A mystery man strides across the kitchen]

1326
00:57:07,568 --> 00:57:09,983
[Past the kitchen, into Sam Kwon's lobby]
Oh, here he comes.

1327
00:57:14,876 --> 00:57:17,719
[Could this be... a kitchen senior?]

1328
00:57:19,480 --> 00:57:21,249
[Whoosh]

1329
00:57:21,249 --> 00:57:23,818
[The mystery man coolly heads on his way]

1330
00:57:23,818 --> 00:57:26,788
- What?
- He just walked past without a word.

1331
00:57:26,788 --> 00:57:28,322
[Peek]

1332
00:57:28,322 --> 00:57:29,891
Right there I got a little spooked.

1333
00:57:29,891 --> 00:57:31,449
[Heads up alone in the elevator]
So you...

1334
00:57:33,161 --> 00:57:37,906
[At this point... wrong start date maybe?]

1335
00:57:38,791 --> 00:57:44,906
[While Sam Kwon spirals
into confusion alone...]

1336
00:57:44,906 --> 00:57:48,242
[Swoosh]

1337
00:57:48,242 --> 00:57:51,371
- A kick scooter.
- So that's how he commutes. Had no idea.

1338
00:57:53,481 --> 00:57:54,981
Hello.

1339
00:57:55,650 --> 00:57:57,051
Hello.

1340
00:57:57,785 --> 00:57:59,120
[The mystery scooter guy breezes past]

1341
00:57:59,120 --> 00:58:01,155
Nobody's even...

1342
00:58:01,155 --> 00:58:03,764
They don't know I work here.

1343
00:58:04,459 --> 00:58:06,305
- Why didn't you say hi?
- Did I come too early?

1344
00:58:06,305 --> 00:58:08,129
I said hi.

1345
00:58:08,129 --> 00:58:09,730
He thought I was crew and just nodded.

1346
00:58:09,730 --> 00:58:11,231
[A first-day morning unlike what he expected]

1347
00:58:13,201 --> 00:58:15,006
[Sam Kwon, today's new rookie]
But surprisingly,

1348
00:58:15,006 --> 00:58:17,038
nobody seems all that interested in me.

1349
00:58:17,038 --> 00:58:19,107
[Why was no one paying you attention?]
I really can't say.

1350
00:58:19,107 --> 00:58:21,344
I honestly have no clue...

1351
00:58:22,376 --> 00:58:24,846
- Why won't anyone talk to me?
- A little different

1352
00:58:24,846 --> 00:58:26,614
[Cute]
from the confident attitude earlier.

1353
00:58:26,614 --> 00:58:29,984
- Just a little bit...
- I also had no clue if they were even staff.

1354
00:58:29,984 --> 00:58:31,819
How would a non-employee end up here...

1355
00:58:31,819 --> 00:58:33,421
Right, like, I had no idea

1356
00:58:33,421 --> 00:58:35,156
[Sam Kwah, new hire]
if they were floor staff or kitchen staff.

1357
00:58:35,156 --> 00:58:36,436
- So you didn't know?
- Or the boss, who knows.

1358
00:58:36,436 --> 00:58:37,892
I had zero clue, no information at all.

1359
00:58:37,892 --> 00:58:39,660
[Poor thing]

1360
00:58:39,660 --> 00:58:43,272
[Pacing with hands
politely clasped for a while]

1361
00:58:44,165 --> 00:58:45,766
- Hello.
- Hello.

1362
00:58:45,766 --> 00:58:47,034
[Trailing along]
Hello.

1363
00:58:47,969 --> 00:58:49,871
[Trailing along]
Hello.

1364
00:58:49,871 --> 00:58:51,639
The boss is finally here.

1365
00:58:51,639 --> 00:58:53,508
I'm Sam.

1366
00:58:53,508 --> 00:58:55,810
- I'm Luisa.
- I'm Laura.

1367
00:58:55,810 --> 00:58:57,345
Welcome.

1368
00:58:57,345 --> 00:58:58,418
Welcome.

1369
00:58:58,418 --> 00:58:59,714
[Finally getting a warm welcome]

1370
00:58:59,714 --> 00:59:01,849
I'm the one starting work here today.

1371
00:59:01,849 --> 00:59:03,851
- Okay.
- Okay.

1372
00:59:03,851 --> 00:59:05,720
[A kind smile]
- Okay. - Okay.

1373
00:59:05,720 --> 00:59:09,223
Let's change clothes first,

1374
00:59:09,223 --> 00:59:11,458
- Okay.
- and we start.

1375
00:59:12,493 --> 00:59:14,996
[The guy who walked past earlier]
- The one from before. - Yes.

1376
00:59:14,996 --> 00:59:16,063
[So you're the new rookie all along]

1377
00:59:16,063 --> 00:59:17,865
[Flustered]
He had no idea.

1378
00:59:17,865 --> 00:59:20,234
- This is Paolo.
- Nice to meet you, I'm Sam.

1379
00:59:20,234 --> 00:59:22,803
- This is Sam.
- Sam.

1380
00:59:22,803 --> 00:59:24,138
- Sam.
- Sam.

1381
00:59:24,138 --> 00:59:26,407
[Replaying the rookie's name out of guilt]

1382
00:59:26,407 --> 00:59:27,975
So awkward.

1383
00:59:27,975 --> 00:59:30,444
[Wild introductions done, off to the kitchen!]
We need two minutes.

1384
00:59:30,444 --> 00:59:31,944
Okay.

1385
00:59:32,933 --> 00:59:35,750
- Come on in.
- Okay. Thank you.

1386
00:59:35,750 --> 00:59:38,233
This is our kitchen.

1387
00:59:40,228 --> 00:59:42,490
[Sam Kwon's five-day undercover kitchen]
Looked pretty spacious, no?

1388
00:59:42,490 --> 00:59:44,692
That's basically the whole thing.

1389
00:59:44,692 --> 00:59:46,894
- Oh, smaller than it looked?
- Yeah, really small.

1390
00:59:46,894 --> 00:59:50,631
The space is small,
but it's got everything we need.

1391
00:59:52,266 --> 00:59:54,101
[Surprised]
- Still, eight burners. - Right.

1392
00:59:54,101 --> 00:59:56,604
Which means all eight are needed.

1393
00:59:56,604 --> 00:59:58,472
[Check!]
Right.

1394
00:59:58,472 --> 01:00:00,708
This is where we make pasta every day.

1395
01:00:00,708 --> 01:00:02,677
[Pasta Station]

1396
01:00:02,677 --> 01:00:03,978
[At the pasta station]
Here's the pasta station.

1397
01:00:03,978 --> 01:00:05,079
[Pasta noodles by type]

1398
01:00:05,079 --> 01:00:07,118
- All dried pasta here, too.
- All dried.

1399
01:00:07,118 --> 01:00:08,916
[Pasta noodle cooker]

1400
01:00:08,916 --> 01:00:11,738
[And the timers all clustered together]

1401
01:00:12,853 --> 01:00:13,821
[Boil and cook the moment orders come in]

1402
01:00:13,821 --> 01:00:16,190
Every kitchen has its own style,

1403
01:00:16,190 --> 01:00:17,968
- their own routines and all.
- Right.

1404
01:00:17,968 --> 01:00:19,731
[Optimal movement]
I need to learn this.

1405
01:00:19,731 --> 01:00:24,025
[Main part]
Next to that is the main course area.

1406
01:00:24,025 --> 01:00:26,178
- Okay.
- We grill meat here

1407
01:00:26,178 --> 01:00:28,768
and fry food over there.

1408
01:00:30,658 --> 01:00:33,328
This is a fridge for quick access.

1409
01:00:33,328 --> 01:00:35,168
Buongiorno!

1410
01:00:36,935 --> 01:00:40,658
[The person who went up earlier]

1411
01:00:40,658 --> 01:00:41,836
[Turns out he's another kitchen senior]

1412
01:00:41,836 --> 01:00:43,065
- Buongiorno!
- This is Antonio.

1413
01:00:43,065 --> 01:00:44,135
- And this is Sam.
- I'm Sam.

1414
01:00:44,135 --> 01:00:45,275
People from Naples.

1415
01:00:45,275 --> 01:00:46,825
[Awkward greeting...]

1416
01:00:46,825 --> 01:00:48,805
[Glance]
Antonio's style is very...

1417
01:00:48,805 --> 01:00:50,215
He's cool, right?

1418
01:00:50,215 --> 01:00:54,685
- He's being wary.
- We divided the fridges according to the needs.

1419
01:00:54,685 --> 01:00:57,406
[Unaware of the senior's curious gaze]
- Naples style. - Oh, really?

1420
01:00:57,406 --> 01:00:59,175
Here we find...

1421
01:00:59,175 --> 01:01:01,145
[Politely clasping hands]
Here are the second dishes.

1422
01:01:01,145 --> 01:01:03,729
[Listening with focused eyes]
Here are the second dishes.

1423
01:01:03,729 --> 01:01:04,567
Okay.

1424
01:01:04,567 --> 01:01:07,654
[At the focused junior, Chef Luisa continues the tour]
This side of the work...

1425
01:01:07,654 --> 01:01:11,032
This is where Antonio mainly works.

1426
01:01:11,032 --> 01:01:12,107
[Welcome to my zone]

1427
01:01:12,107 --> 01:01:14,412
You can see he's nervous in the kitchen.

1428
01:01:14,412 --> 01:01:15,658
- Right.
- Yes.

1429
01:01:15,658 --> 01:01:19,892
Appetizer and dessert ingredients

1430
01:01:19,892 --> 01:01:21,376
- are here.
- Okay.

1431
01:01:21,376 --> 01:01:25,463
You'll understand the system

1432
01:01:25,463 --> 01:01:27,294
- once you try.
- Yes.

1433
01:01:27,294 --> 01:01:32,345
- Okay. Sam, look around more with Antonio.
- Okay. Follow me.

1434
01:01:32,345 --> 01:01:34,405
Thank you.

1435
01:01:34,405 --> 01:01:38,445
[From here, Antonio takes the lead]

1436
01:01:38,445 --> 01:01:40,665
[Following Antonio]
[Passing through the narrow kitchen aisles]

1437
01:01:40,665 --> 01:01:41,785
It's a long way.

1438
01:01:41,785 --> 01:01:44,635
[Observing the long path carefully]
It's very long.

1439
01:01:44,635 --> 01:01:48,075
[Silently]
[Antonio leads him to a back corner]

1440
01:01:48,075 --> 01:01:50,425
[Shooing]
Please, Antonio.

1441
01:01:50,425 --> 01:01:51,685
[Door opens]

1442
01:01:51,685 --> 01:01:52,725
[Get in?]
- Get in. - That senior's...

1443
01:01:52,725 --> 01:01:53,765
His gaze is quite intense.

1444
01:01:53,765 --> 01:01:55,165
- Right?
- Antonio.

1445
01:01:55,165 --> 01:01:57,735
[Boarding with the intense senior]
That senior seems a bit...

1446
01:01:57,735 --> 01:01:59,205
He seems like a tough one.

1447
01:01:59,205 --> 01:02:01,815
[Presses 2nd floor]

1448
01:02:01,815 --> 01:02:03,165
- How are you?
- Good...

1449
01:02:03,165 --> 01:02:05,803
- Are you nervous?
- A little bit.

1450
01:02:09,005 --> 01:02:10,565
- The elevator is really slow.
- It's kind of crappy, isn't it?

1451
01:02:10,565 --> 01:02:11,592
The elevator is a bit slow, right?

1452
01:02:11,592 --> 01:02:13,445
- European elevators are a bit slow.
- This is so awkward...

1453
01:02:13,445 --> 01:02:14,708
[In that awkward silence]
It's so slow that...

1454
01:02:14,708 --> 01:02:17,305
The time and space they're sharing
are just so awkward.

1455
01:02:17,305 --> 01:02:21,285
- It's so awkward just going up one floor.
- He's feeling so awkward in that small space.

1456
01:02:21,285 --> 01:02:23,901
- This is the place!
- Okay.

1457
01:02:23,901 --> 01:02:25,175
This is our locker room.

1458
01:02:25,175 --> 01:02:27,133
Change your clothes
and leave your things in a locker.

1459
01:02:27,133 --> 01:02:28,989
[Changing into chef's whites
in the locker room]

1460
01:02:28,989 --> 01:02:30,285
- Wow, this is nice.
- Are you all changed?

1461
01:02:30,285 --> 01:02:32,317
- Yes, sir.
- It looks good on you.

1462
01:02:32,317 --> 01:02:35,195
[Changed and ready, now off to the kitchen!]
Let's start to work.

1463
01:02:35,195 --> 01:02:36,717
Okay.

1464
01:02:36,717 --> 01:02:38,989
[What about this hat?]

1465
01:02:38,989 --> 01:02:40,162
[Cracking up lol]
It's so...

1466
01:02:40,162 --> 01:02:43,082
[Seniors wear majestic chef hats]
It's so Naples-style.

1467
01:02:43,082 --> 01:02:45,066
[Tight]
[The junior's signature hat, a tight bandana]

1468
01:02:45,066 --> 01:02:46,210
Isn't this cutting off the circulation?

1469
01:02:46,210 --> 01:02:47,533
No, no.

1470
01:02:47,533 --> 01:02:49,917
[Solemn]

1471
01:02:49,917 --> 01:02:52,779
[Breathtaking]

1472
01:02:53,725 --> 01:02:56,925
[Kitchen hierarchy clearly defined by the hats]

1473
01:02:56,925 --> 01:02:59,485
A bandana?

1474
01:02:59,485 --> 01:03:01,533
I'll get recognized quickly,

1475
01:03:01,533 --> 01:03:02,635
get promoted,

1476
01:03:02,635 --> 01:03:04,141
and definitely move up.

1477
01:03:04,141 --> 01:03:07,645
[Determined to part ways
with the tight bandana]

1478
01:03:07,645 --> 01:03:11,085
So, Paolo, which station are you in charge of?

1479
01:03:11,085 --> 01:03:14,405
I handle everything when it's busy,

1480
01:03:14,405 --> 01:03:16,157
but during service,
I'm mainly on the main dishes.

1481
01:03:16,157 --> 01:03:18,093
Okay.

1482
01:03:18,893 --> 01:03:22,013
[Kitchen hierarchy]
Ah, kitchen hierarchy is important.

1483
01:03:22,013 --> 01:03:27,869
It's already been 35 years
since we started working together.

1484
01:03:27,869 --> 01:03:29,469
[No. 1 Owner-chefs Luisa & Laura]
Wow, 35 years.

1485
01:03:29,469 --> 01:03:31,917
- This is the third generation.
- The third generation.

1486
01:03:31,917 --> 01:03:34,365
Paolo has been working here for about 16 years.

1487
01:03:34,365 --> 01:03:38,749
Paolo is the epitome of "trust."

1488
01:03:39,485 --> 01:03:40,773
He doesn't just handle main dishes,

1489
01:03:40,773 --> 01:03:44,733
he knows how to work
every station in the kitchen.

1490
01:03:44,733 --> 01:03:46,797
That's not something just anyone can do.

1491
01:03:46,797 --> 01:03:49,469
[Indeed, indeed]
- The restaurant. - I mean, for years.

1492
01:03:49,469 --> 01:03:51,629
After us, he's the one who carries

1493
01:03:51,629 --> 01:03:55,693
the most responsibility for this place.

1494
01:03:55,693 --> 01:03:57,309
[No. 2 Paolo, in charge of main dishes]

1495
01:03:57,309 --> 01:04:00,189
Paolo is really charming.

1496
01:04:00,189 --> 01:04:01,709
And Antonio...

1497
01:04:01,709 --> 01:04:04,637
[28-year-old young blood]
Antonio is the youngest in our team.

1498
01:04:04,637 --> 01:04:06,237
But when it comes to kitchen work,

1499
01:04:06,237 --> 01:04:08,455
he's very smart and driven.

1500
01:04:08,455 --> 01:04:10,397
But on more fronts, like Paolo does.

1501
01:04:10,397 --> 01:04:11,581
A passionate guy.

1502
01:04:11,581 --> 01:04:13,255
He's the youngest. Gen MZ.

1503
01:04:13,255 --> 01:04:15,853
[No. 3 Antonio, Appetizers]
Naples Gen MZ.

1504
01:04:15,853 --> 01:04:17,501
[No. 1 Owner Sisters]
Is this the whole team?

1505
01:04:17,501 --> 01:04:18,717
[No. 2 Paolo]
- This is it. - That's everyone?

1506
01:04:18,717 --> 01:04:20,349
[No. 3 Antonio]
Yes.

1507
01:04:20,349 --> 01:04:23,115
[What will be the role of Sam Kwon,
the new junior?]

1508
01:04:23,115 --> 01:04:25,757
[Junior Sam's Role:
Assigned to Appetizers & Desserts]

1509
01:04:25,757 --> 01:04:28,461
We'll see if he can handle everything
from cooking to plating on his own.

1510
01:04:28,461 --> 01:04:33,853
He must "perfectly master"
appetizers and desserts

1511
01:04:33,853 --> 01:04:35,469
to be eligible for promotion.

1512
01:04:35,469 --> 01:04:38,295
We can move to the next step.

1513
01:04:38,295 --> 01:04:41,757
- It'll take at least six months, right?
- But... Yes.

1514
01:04:41,757 --> 01:04:43,773
Normally, yes, but...

1515
01:04:43,773 --> 01:04:44,893
If he's good...

1516
01:04:44,893 --> 01:04:49,229
it's possible within three months.

1517
01:04:49,229 --> 01:04:51,117
[Can he ditch the bandana in five days?]
It takes three months...

1518
01:04:51,117 --> 01:04:52,957
That won't be easy.

1519
01:04:54,338 --> 01:04:57,506
Shall we have a quick welcome

1520
01:04:57,506 --> 01:05:00,605
before we start?

1521
01:05:00,605 --> 01:05:04,052
To celebrate your first day,
I brought some sweets.

1522
01:05:04,052 --> 01:05:06,125
- What's this?
- Sweets.

1523
01:05:06,125 --> 01:05:07,875
This is also part of Naples culture.

1524
01:05:07,875 --> 01:05:10,558
Let's take a breather since it's day one.

1525
01:05:10,558 --> 01:05:11,885
Wow!

1526
01:05:11,885 --> 01:05:15,899
I brought a variety
since I didn't know what the junior would like.

1527
01:05:19,117 --> 01:05:20,364
[Proud]

1528
01:05:20,364 --> 01:05:22,942
Cakes and desserts...

1529
01:05:22,942 --> 01:05:24,333
- Bringing them like that...
- It looks delicious.

1530
01:05:24,333 --> 01:05:25,953
- is their culture to eat together.
- Is it?

1531
01:05:25,953 --> 01:05:28,285
But why don't you bring us

1532
01:05:28,285 --> 01:05:29,773
- sweets or desserts?
- Because we're in Seoul.

1533
01:05:29,773 --> 01:05:31,583
You said you're a Neapolitan!

1534
01:05:31,583 --> 01:05:35,197
[Sam Kwon / Lived there 9 months]
I'm Neapolitan only in Naples.

1535
01:05:35,197 --> 01:05:37,485
- Okay.
- Please.

1536
01:05:41,437 --> 01:05:43,037
Paolo, which flavor do you want?

1537
01:05:43,037 --> 01:05:44,425
I'll have...

1538
01:05:44,425 --> 01:05:46,701
- Chocolate.
- Chocolate.

1539
01:05:46,701 --> 01:05:48,973
[Awkwardly waiting for seniors to pick]
- Okay, please. - Thank you.

1540
01:05:48,973 --> 01:05:50,102
And you, Laura?

1541
01:05:50,102 --> 01:05:52,745
- I'll take cream!
- Okay.

1542
01:05:52,745 --> 01:05:55,808
[Everyone picks a flavor]
- Looks good. - Looks good.

1543
01:05:56,567 --> 01:05:58,813
It's a good day for all of us.

1544
01:05:58,813 --> 01:06:00,829
Happy first day.

1545
01:06:00,829 --> 01:06:01,895
It's quite relaxed, right?

1546
01:06:01,895 --> 01:06:03,677
[Thank you...] [Touched]
It's a bit different, isn't it?

1547
01:06:03,677 --> 01:06:06,237
[A simple, warm welcome snack party]
It's so relaxed.

1548
01:06:06,237 --> 01:06:08,685
Wait, you can speak Italian?

1549
01:06:08,685 --> 01:06:10,157
- Just a little!
- A little bit.

1550
01:06:10,157 --> 01:06:12,189
But...

1551
01:06:12,189 --> 01:06:14,461
The Naples dialect is...

1552
01:06:14,461 --> 01:06:16,893
[Agreed]
- Ah, yes. - It's a little...

1553
01:06:16,893 --> 01:06:18,555
The dialect is quite intense.

1554
01:06:18,555 --> 01:06:20,253
In Korea, it's like Gyeongsang-do.

1555
01:06:20,253 --> 01:06:21,341
- Is it like that dialect?
- It's more than that.

1556
01:06:21,341 --> 01:06:23,021
- It's more like the Jeju dialect.
- Oh, really?

1557
01:06:23,021 --> 01:06:25,085
[Chatting while eating welcome snacks]

1558
01:06:25,085 --> 01:06:28,248
Is this how you spell your name?

1559
01:06:29,757 --> 01:06:32,215
[Like this?]
[KWON]

1560
01:06:32,215 --> 01:06:33,437
How do you pronounce it?

1561
01:06:33,437 --> 01:06:35,645
How do you pronounce it?

1562
01:06:35,645 --> 01:06:37,229
- Kwon!
- Quon.

1563
01:06:37,229 --> 01:06:39,037
- Kwon!
- Kwon-ne.

1564
01:06:39,037 --> 01:06:41,005
- Kwon-ne.
- Kwon-ne.

1565
01:06:41,005 --> 01:06:43,202
[Everyone is busy learning the junior's name]
[Buzzing]

1566
01:06:46,237 --> 01:06:48,317
- Kwon-ne.
- Kwon-ne.

1567
01:06:48,317 --> 01:06:51,213
[Suddenly a name tag?]

1568
01:06:51,213 --> 01:06:53,582
I'll put this on Kwon's locker.

1569
01:06:53,582 --> 01:06:54,749
Shall we go together?

1570
01:06:54,749 --> 01:06:57,165
- Me too?
- Yes, yes.

1571
01:06:57,165 --> 01:06:59,485
[Drops the bread and rushes off]

1572
01:06:59,485 --> 01:07:01,131
They're very relaxed.

1573
01:07:01,131 --> 01:07:03,149
I know, and they're so kind.

1574
01:07:03,149 --> 01:07:04,426
- Even putting a name on the locker...
- So kind.

1575
01:07:04,426 --> 01:07:06,845
[Kwon... Kuwon... Kwon]
It's different here in Naples.

1576
01:07:06,845 --> 01:07:07,837
Paolo?

1577
01:07:07,837 --> 01:07:08,941
- Paolo!
- Paolo.

1578
01:07:08,941 --> 01:07:10,525
[Introduction time in the slow elevator]
Paolo Pirozzi.

1579
01:07:10,525 --> 01:07:12,775
Are there no stairs here then?

1580
01:07:12,775 --> 01:07:15,645
- Why? Are you frustrated?
- Yeah.

1581
01:07:15,645 --> 01:07:18,019
[Frustrated]
Save your knee joints.

1582
01:07:18,019 --> 01:07:20,067
[I want to run up the stairs...]
Save your knees.

1583
01:07:23,629 --> 01:07:25,405
[Senior is the best]
That's perfect.

1584
01:07:25,405 --> 01:07:27,005
He already set it up like this.

1585
01:07:27,005 --> 01:07:29,405
Seeing that would make me feel recognized.

1586
01:07:29,405 --> 01:07:34,093
[You're an official member now]
Now it is official.

1587
01:07:34,093 --> 01:07:36,909
Shall I explain what to do today?

1588
01:07:36,909 --> 01:07:38,269
Yes.

1589
01:07:38,269 --> 01:07:41,469
This is the board where we write our tasks.

1590
01:07:41,469 --> 01:07:42,525
[Today's to-do]
It begins now.

1591
01:07:42,525 --> 01:07:45,805
[A board for tasks during prep time]
For the moment it is...

1592
01:07:45,805 --> 01:07:50,429
Now Paolo will bring the pot for potatoes.

1593
01:07:50,429 --> 01:07:51,605
[First task for the kitchen junior:]

1594
01:07:51,605 --> 01:07:53,725
[Preparing potatoes]
Potatoes.

1595
01:07:53,725 --> 01:07:57,997
The potatoes we prep today go in the cake.

1596
01:07:57,997 --> 01:08:00,907
[Naples-style potato cake on the menu]
- It's a Napoli preparation. - Potato cake?

1597
01:08:00,907 --> 01:08:03,341
That's a traditional Naples dish.

1598
01:08:04,024 --> 01:08:06,845
[Naples sausage and leafy greens layered between potatoes]
It's a cake, but it has vegetables

1599
01:08:06,845 --> 01:08:08,125
and sausage in it.

1600
01:08:08,125 --> 01:08:09,501
Sounds delicious.

1601
01:08:09,501 --> 01:08:11,869
- It sounds delicious.
- It's really good!

1602
01:08:11,869 --> 01:08:13,181
I'll have to learn how to make it.

1603
01:08:13,181 --> 01:08:14,701
That's right, you're here to learn!

1604
01:08:14,701 --> 01:08:16,621
[Eyes of a passionate kitchen junior]

1605
01:08:16,621 --> 01:08:18,077
We say that it's passed down

1606
01:08:18,077 --> 01:08:20,685
[Coffee is served]
from hand to hand.

1607
01:08:20,685 --> 01:08:21,835
Oh, coffee.

1608
01:08:21,835 --> 01:08:23,133
Laura, just a little for me.

1609
01:08:23,133 --> 01:08:25,365
I've already had three cups this morning.

1610
01:08:25,365 --> 01:08:27,613
- Only three?
- Only three.

1611
01:08:28,509 --> 01:08:31,997
[Having his third cup of coffee]
But the morning is so relaxed here.

1612
01:08:31,997 --> 01:08:34,749
[After the 3rd coffee...]
Shouldn't they be prepping and teaching?

1613
01:08:34,749 --> 01:08:36,577
[Time to work]

1614
01:08:36,577 --> 01:08:38,475
Now, let's go get the potatoes.

1615
01:08:38,475 --> 01:08:39,949
Okay.

1616
01:08:39,949 --> 01:08:41,945
- Let's get to work. Fighting!
- Okay.

1617
01:08:41,945 --> 01:08:44,109
Over here!

1618
01:08:44,109 --> 01:08:45,725
[Awkward]

1619
01:08:45,725 --> 01:08:48,733
Oh, the storage room was outside!

1620
01:08:48,733 --> 01:08:50,975
[Following Paolo across the yard]

1621
01:08:52,618 --> 01:08:53,629
Okay.

1622
01:08:53,629 --> 01:08:56,509
[Heaving a sack of potatoes]

1623
01:08:56,509 --> 01:08:57,741
[Receiving a sack of potatoes]

1624
01:08:57,741 --> 01:08:59,416
[Another sack?]

1625
01:08:59,416 --> 01:09:01,117
Two sacks of potatoes?

1626
01:09:01,117 --> 01:09:02,317
- Oh my, you use two whole sacks?
- We're using two sacks right now.

1627
01:09:02,317 --> 01:09:03,981
That dish must be very popular.

1628
01:09:03,981 --> 01:09:06,797
[What will they do with all these?]
I wondered why they needed so many.

1629
01:09:06,797 --> 01:09:08,861
For such a small restaurant.

1630
01:09:08,861 --> 01:09:11,371
[Each carrying a sack of potatoes]

1631
01:09:12,125 --> 01:09:13,666
[Dumping them all out]

1632
01:09:13,666 --> 01:09:15,125
Okay.

1633
01:09:15,125 --> 01:09:17,117
[Followed by a vigorous washing]

1634
01:09:17,117 --> 01:09:19,517
- Yes, it's fine.
- Okay.

1635
01:09:21,213 --> 01:09:23,085
Okay.

1636
01:09:23,085 --> 01:09:25,613
[Heavy, wet potatoes]

1637
01:09:25,613 --> 01:09:28,653
[filling two whole pots]
The amount is unbelievable.

1638
01:09:28,653 --> 01:09:30,525
- No salt?
- Don't add anything!

1639
01:09:30,525 --> 01:09:32,285
No salt at all?

1640
01:09:32,285 --> 01:09:35,949
[Waiting for the potatoes to boil]

1641
01:09:35,949 --> 01:09:38,109
I thought they were doing it for show.

1642
01:09:38,109 --> 01:09:39,515
[Surprised by the amount]
They really used it all.

1643
01:09:39,515 --> 01:09:42,061
Not everyone does things for show like you.

1644
01:09:42,061 --> 01:09:45,373
[The secret of the potatoes is?]
At that time, I was still suspicious.

1645
01:09:45,373 --> 01:09:48,189
This is friarielli. Shall we carry it?

1646
01:09:48,795 --> 01:09:50,413
- They are nice.
- What kind of vegetable is that?

1647
01:09:50,413 --> 01:09:51,548
Nice.

1648
01:09:51,548 --> 01:09:53,424
- We put them...
- Friarielli.

1649
01:09:53,424 --> 01:09:54,807
It's not available in Korea.

1650
01:09:54,807 --> 01:09:56,875
Let's arrange them like this.

1651
01:09:56,875 --> 01:09:59,149
[This vegetable is unfamiliar to us]

1652
01:09:59,149 --> 01:10:02,077
[One of Naples' representative specialties]
It's a vegetable eaten a lot in Naples.

1653
01:10:02,077 --> 01:10:05,485
[Tastes similar to Korean radish greens]
It tastes a bit like radish greens.

1654
01:10:07,469 --> 01:10:09,885
[Used in various ways
from appetizers to main dishes]

1655
01:10:09,885 --> 01:10:12,973
It's a very important vegetable in Naples.

1656
01:10:12,973 --> 01:10:17,229
[A staple ingredient on Neapolitan tables]

1657
01:10:17,229 --> 01:10:19,945
[Second task: Trimming friarielli]
So, I'll explain to you.

1658
01:10:19,945 --> 01:10:22,045
First, watch what I do.

1659
01:10:22,642 --> 01:10:23,867
See these young shoots?

1660
01:10:23,867 --> 01:10:26,142
You pluck them off by hand like this.

1661
01:10:26,142 --> 01:10:27,485
See these young shoots?

1662
01:10:27,485 --> 01:10:28,978
You pluck them off

1663
01:10:28,978 --> 01:10:30,482
[Delicious]
by hand like this.

1664
01:10:30,482 --> 01:10:31,906
[Must keep]
You must take them.

1665
01:10:31,906 --> 01:10:35,106
And there's a stem in the middle.

1666
01:10:35,106 --> 01:10:38,112
[Friarielli stem]

1667
01:10:38,112 --> 01:10:41,394
This part is especially tasty,

1668
01:10:41,394 --> 01:10:43,746
[Focusing]
so make sure to save it.

1669
01:10:43,746 --> 01:10:46,210
[After Luisa's crash course]
You break it like this.

1670
01:10:46,210 --> 01:10:48,562
You take the whole and put it there.

1671
01:10:48,562 --> 01:10:51,106
[Now it's Kwon's turn to try]
Okay.

1672
01:10:51,106 --> 01:10:52,194
[Interested]

1673
01:10:52,194 --> 01:10:53,634
Now you show me how it's done.

1674
01:10:54,642 --> 01:10:56,306
[Let's see how good the Kitchen junior]
Take from here.

1675
01:10:56,306 --> 01:10:59,882
As if it were a flower.

1676
01:10:59,882 --> 01:11:01,490
[Sparkling eyes]

1677
01:11:02,295 --> 01:11:04,278
Aren't they like a couple?

1678
01:11:04,278 --> 01:11:06,159
Why is he looking at me like that?

1679
01:11:07,410 --> 01:11:10,866
[Staring intently...]
As if you held a flower.

1680
01:11:10,866 --> 01:11:12,770
You leaf through that way.

1681
01:11:12,770 --> 01:11:14,610
[All eyes are on Kwon]
Okay.

1682
01:11:14,610 --> 01:11:16,930
You pull, and pull, and take it.

1683
01:11:17,810 --> 01:11:21,058
[He starts trimming with determination]
Some are... Good.

1684
01:11:21,058 --> 01:11:22,834
Some are... Good.

1685
01:11:22,834 --> 01:11:24,898
- Is this okay?
- Yes, good job.

1686
01:11:24,898 --> 01:11:29,074
[Showing off his skills as promised?]
- The stem should never be double. - Okay.

1687
01:11:29,074 --> 01:11:30,352
Okay.

1688
01:11:30,352 --> 01:11:31,842
[That's it, good job]
Okay.

1689
01:11:33,212 --> 01:11:35,026
[Nodding]

1690
01:11:35,026 --> 01:11:37,091
Good job, okay.

1691
01:11:38,158 --> 01:11:39,914
Wow, he's good.

1692
01:11:40,898 --> 01:11:42,674
[Sudden self-praise]
He's praising himself.

1693
01:11:42,674 --> 01:11:44,178
No, I'm just saying...

1694
01:11:44,178 --> 01:11:45,579
We'll be the ones to say that.

1695
01:11:45,579 --> 01:11:47,642
Well, Since no one says it,
I have to say it myself.

1696
01:11:47,642 --> 01:11:49,202
It's because you don't seem that good.

1697
01:11:49,202 --> 01:11:51,954
[He only plucked one leaf so far...]

1698
01:11:51,954 --> 01:11:54,594
[A constant stream of compliments]
Good job, okay.

1699
01:11:54,594 --> 01:11:57,170
[Perfect from the first try?]
That, too.

1700
01:11:57,170 --> 01:11:58,850
[Miss]

1701
01:11:58,850 --> 01:12:01,602
[He just ripped the leaf part off]

1702
01:12:04,530 --> 01:12:06,242
[Oh, no]
Look, that's why I say leaf through.

1703
01:12:06,242 --> 01:12:07,458
[Give it back!]
Do you know why?

1704
01:12:07,458 --> 01:12:11,394
[Failed to get it right at once...]
So you don't get confused.

1705
01:12:11,394 --> 01:12:13,794
[Disappointed]

1706
01:12:13,794 --> 01:12:15,922
Good at what?

1707
01:12:15,922 --> 01:12:17,442
So close...

1708
01:12:17,442 --> 01:12:19,330
Is this your first time seeing this ingredient?

1709
01:12:19,330 --> 01:12:20,818
No, I've used it a lot.

1710
01:12:20,818 --> 01:12:22,450
Are you doing that on purpose?

1711
01:12:22,450 --> 01:12:23,634
Not on purpose.

1712
01:12:23,634 --> 01:12:25,954
I just wasn't rushing it back then.

1713
01:12:25,954 --> 01:12:27,522
- To build a narrative...
- Right.

1714
01:12:27,522 --> 01:12:28,930
Your expression is getting...

1715
01:12:28,930 --> 01:12:30,508
He's getting nervous now.

1716
01:12:30,508 --> 01:12:33,712
[Nervous as mistakes are pointed out]
- I was nervous. - Because it's a real job.

1717
01:12:33,712 --> 01:12:35,922
You clean it all.

1718
01:12:35,922 --> 01:12:37,922
You take out those.

1719
01:12:37,922 --> 01:12:39,314
[Attention]
That's why I say you do like that.

1720
01:12:39,314 --> 01:12:41,874
[Luisa kindly explains again]
As if it were...

1721
01:12:41,874 --> 01:12:44,514
[Focusing again!]
You take off...

1722
01:12:44,514 --> 01:12:45,634
- Okay?
- Okay.

1723
01:12:45,634 --> 01:12:46,946
Want to try again?

1724
01:12:46,946 --> 01:12:49,090
[Retrying with determination]

1725
01:12:51,794 --> 01:12:54,258
[Observing closely]

1726
01:12:55,154 --> 01:12:58,702
[No second mistakes]
Okay.

1727
01:13:00,222 --> 01:13:01,495
Bravo!

1728
01:13:02,762 --> 01:13:04,722
You're really fast and good.

1729
01:13:04,722 --> 01:13:06,418
[Hehe]

1730
01:13:06,418 --> 01:13:07,522
I'm just trying my best.

1731
01:13:07,522 --> 01:13:09,292
[Napoli Matfia's rare humility]

1732
01:13:09,292 --> 01:13:10,594
[Confidence button ON]

1733
01:13:10,594 --> 01:13:12,047
[Confidence button OFF for the boss]

1734
01:13:13,058 --> 01:13:15,698
[And the two senior chefs are watching]

1735
01:13:17,474 --> 01:13:20,178
Look at Antonio now.

1736
01:13:20,178 --> 01:13:21,762
He's making appetizers.

1737
01:13:21,762 --> 01:13:24,706
Look at Antonio. He's making appetizers now.

1738
01:13:24,706 --> 01:13:26,242
- Appetizers?
- Yes.

1739
01:13:26,242 --> 01:13:27,826
What is Antonio making right now?

1740
01:13:27,826 --> 01:13:29,874
[Provola Pancetta di Riso, Rice Cake]
I take the provola for the rice.

1741
01:13:29,874 --> 01:13:32,672
Not the provola, the bacon for the rice.

1742
01:13:33,362 --> 01:13:36,642
[Wary of Senior Chef Antonio's chicness]

1743
01:13:36,642 --> 01:13:42,602
Kwon, I have other things to do, so I'll go.

1744
01:13:42,602 --> 01:13:45,602
Get ready for service with
Laura, Paolo, and Antonio.

1745
01:13:45,602 --> 01:13:46,926
Okay.

1746
01:13:47,602 --> 01:13:49,918
They're all good people, so don't worry.

1747
01:13:52,258 --> 01:13:54,434
You're in good hands.

1748
01:13:55,602 --> 01:13:59,346
[10:00 AM. Luisa leaves the kitchen]

1749
01:14:00,012 --> 01:14:04,172
[Friarielli prep is finished]
Okay. Friarielli is over.

1750
01:14:04,172 --> 01:14:07,391
[Checking the boiled potatoes]
They're almost done.

1751
01:14:07,391 --> 01:14:10,082
[Third task for the Commis chef: Peeling]
We have those as well,

1752
01:14:10,082 --> 01:14:12,386
and we use them for the potatoes. Okay?

1753
01:14:12,386 --> 01:14:16,032
[Two pots of boiled potatoes to be peeled]

1754
01:14:16,690 --> 01:14:19,698
[This huge amount is only for two days!]

1755
01:14:20,770 --> 01:14:23,362
[This won't be an easy task...]

1756
01:14:24,482 --> 01:14:28,786
Antonio! Can you move the potatoes
from the small pot now?

1757
01:14:28,786 --> 01:14:30,085
Yes.

1758
01:14:30,914 --> 01:14:34,402
[Peeling potatoes with Senior Antonio?]

1759
01:14:37,202 --> 01:14:40,609
[Senior Antonio stops his knife work and turns]

1760
01:14:41,986 --> 01:14:43,452
It's hot. Do you have a towel?

1761
01:14:43,452 --> 01:14:44,818
[Nods]

1762
01:14:44,818 --> 01:14:47,650
[With a skillful gesture] [Whoosh]

1763
01:14:48,706 --> 01:14:52,592
[Junior, here come the potatoes]

1764
01:14:54,178 --> 01:14:56,338
- Wait, they need to cool down.
- Okay.

1765
01:14:58,274 --> 01:15:01,522
[He coolly moves the potatoes and returns...]

1766
01:15:02,578 --> 01:15:04,850
[Now, Laura's crash course on potato peeling]
We take...

1767
01:15:04,850 --> 01:15:06,379
We take this one.

1768
01:15:07,634 --> 01:15:11,106
The potatoes are hot, so wear gloves.

1769
01:15:11,106 --> 01:15:14,723
And you should only peel the skin like this.

1770
01:15:15,362 --> 01:15:18,818
[Potatoes with only the skin peeled off]
- Okay? - Okay.

1771
01:15:19,714 --> 01:15:22,434
- Then put them here to cool.
- Okay.

1772
01:15:24,274 --> 01:15:27,906
[Putting on gloves first]

1773
01:15:27,906 --> 01:15:30,418
[Napoli Matfia, ready for action]

1774
01:15:31,346 --> 01:15:35,682
[Confidently putting on gloves]

1775
01:15:36,562 --> 01:15:40,034
[The cooking survival winner
starts peeling potatoes]

1776
01:15:42,754 --> 01:15:45,458
[Slip]

1777
01:15:46,066 --> 01:15:48,930
[He quickly checks his surroundings]

1778
01:15:49,562 --> 01:15:52,690
[He starts peeling again
as if nothing happened]

1779
01:15:53,632 --> 01:15:56,578
[The potato flesh is being shaved away]

1780
01:15:59,402 --> 01:16:01,586
What's this? You're shaving off all the flesh!

1781
01:16:01,586 --> 01:16:02,862
No, no.

1782
01:16:02,862 --> 01:16:05,202
- The time...
- That's not a potato, it's a taro now.

1783
01:16:05,202 --> 01:16:08,668
- It's shrunk to the size of a taro.
- No, no.

1784
01:16:10,082 --> 01:16:13,102
[The potatoes are being cut away in chunks...]

1785
01:16:13,842 --> 01:16:15,250
[Our junior...]

1786
01:16:16,194 --> 01:16:18,818
[Is he doing okay?]

1787
01:16:20,242 --> 01:16:23,314
[The potatoes look a bit...]

1788
01:16:25,314 --> 01:16:28,802
[Caught on Senior Antonio's radar?]

1789
01:16:31,986 --> 01:16:35,170
[Senior Antonio approaches Kwon...]

1790
01:16:36,306 --> 01:16:38,626
[Kwon senses someone behind him]

1791
01:16:39,452 --> 01:16:41,042
Should I help?

1792
01:16:41,042 --> 01:16:42,290
Yes...

1793
01:16:44,594 --> 01:16:48,290
[He steps in to help peel the potatoes...]

1794
01:16:50,546 --> 01:16:52,114
[Scrape]

1795
01:16:52,114 --> 01:16:53,474
[Surprised]

1796
01:16:54,066 --> 01:16:56,722
[Peeling potatoes like a machine]

1797
01:16:56,722 --> 01:16:58,178
He had a unique way of peeling them.

1798
01:16:58,178 --> 01:17:00,812
- He peels them like that.
- Like he's gently coaxing it.

1799
01:17:00,812 --> 01:17:03,090
In Korean terms, it's like peeling ginger.

1800
01:17:03,090 --> 01:17:05,422
Peel it like ginger.

1801
01:17:05,422 --> 01:17:07,051
It's easier to scrape it off like this.

1802
01:17:07,051 --> 01:17:08,642
Okay.

1803
01:17:08,642 --> 01:17:11,842
[Scraping only the skin
without wasting any flesh]

1804
01:17:12,578 --> 01:17:13,906
[Coolly tosses it aside]

1805
01:17:14,546 --> 01:17:15,938
[Glance]

1806
01:17:15,938 --> 01:17:17,794
You're so fast.

1807
01:17:18,786 --> 01:17:22,583
If it peels off like this,
it's better to use your hands.

1808
01:17:25,698 --> 01:17:27,727
The way you taught me is better.

1809
01:17:30,130 --> 01:17:34,178
[He might actually be a kind senior...]

1810
01:17:34,882 --> 01:17:37,330
[Potato peeling done with Antonio's help]
- We prepare it in the bigger pan. - Okay.

1811
01:17:37,330 --> 01:17:40,578
[And now, opening the big pot]

1812
01:17:40,578 --> 01:17:43,746
[Working together to move the hot pot]

1813
01:17:43,746 --> 01:17:45,033
Perfect.

1814
01:17:45,906 --> 01:17:48,450
When you hold the handle of a hot pot,

1815
01:17:48,450 --> 01:17:50,460
you have to fold the dishcloth properly.

1816
01:17:50,460 --> 01:17:52,611
[Antonio's Rule 1. Fold dishcloths neatly]
- Arranged them as well as possible. - Okay.

1817
01:17:52,611 --> 01:17:55,401
Otherwise you have less grip.

1818
01:17:55,401 --> 01:17:56,578
Okay.

1819
01:17:56,578 --> 01:18:00,453
[Cooling potatoes while learning from Antonio]

1820
01:18:02,994 --> 01:18:06,434
[The junior takes a breather with some water]

1821
01:18:07,298 --> 01:18:09,282
[Antonio's eyes are constantly on Kwon]

1822
01:18:10,514 --> 01:18:13,367
It's better to place the water cup
like this if possible.

1823
01:18:14,008 --> 01:18:18,386
This way, the bottle won't
fall and you won't lose the cup.

1824
01:18:18,386 --> 01:18:21,650
[Antonio's Rule 2.
Place your water cup like this.]

1825
01:18:21,650 --> 01:18:24,562
[How to peel potatoes...]

1826
01:18:24,562 --> 01:18:26,922
[How to fold a dishcloth...]

1827
01:18:26,922 --> 01:18:30,290
[Kind Antonio even teaches him
where to put his water cup]

1828
01:18:30,946 --> 01:18:34,754
[This is what life as a junior is like...]

1829
01:18:35,874 --> 01:18:37,823
He's teaching you everything one by one.

1830
01:18:37,823 --> 01:18:40,658
He's... quite kind, wouldn't you say?

1831
01:18:40,658 --> 01:18:42,112
- He is kind.
- Very kind.

1832
01:18:42,112 --> 01:18:44,084
- Why? Did that offend you?
- No, not at all.

1833
01:18:44,084 --> 01:18:47,362
- There's a bit of a sting in your words.
- I really liked it.

1834
01:18:47,362 --> 01:18:48,754
Something seems a bit off, right?

1835
01:18:48,754 --> 01:18:50,830
- I'm so curious.
- No, really.

1836
01:18:51,538 --> 01:18:52,658
Can I start again now?

1837
01:18:52,658 --> 01:18:54,112
Yes, go ahead.

1838
01:18:54,112 --> 01:18:55,164
I closed the water

1839
01:18:55,164 --> 01:18:58,114
[Potato peeling resumes]
so the potatoes are cooling down

1840
01:18:58,114 --> 01:19:00,898
[Don't stop now. Finish the potatoes.]
and start breaking.

1841
01:19:00,898 --> 01:19:02,274
- Okay?
- Okay.

1842
01:19:02,978 --> 01:19:04,690
[Concentrating]

1843
01:19:09,818 --> 01:19:12,900
Usually, you'd follow the method
your senior taught you exactly.

1844
01:19:12,900 --> 01:19:14,898
- But he's stubbornly doing it his way?
- Exactly.

1845
01:19:14,898 --> 01:19:17,082
His senior just showed him how to do it,
but then...

1846
01:19:17,082 --> 01:19:18,578
[Scrape]
He keeps doing it like this.

1847
01:19:18,578 --> 01:19:20,690
He's peeling it like a banana.

1848
01:19:20,690 --> 01:19:22,450
[Scrape, scrape]

1849
01:19:22,450 --> 01:19:25,618
[I'm going my own way...]

1850
01:19:25,618 --> 01:19:27,950
[Caught red-handed.]
- I was watching him too. - Because...

1851
01:19:27,950 --> 01:19:29,490
- No, because...
- He was just taught.

1852
01:19:29,490 --> 01:19:31,330
- No, because...
- But he's still being...

1853
01:19:31,330 --> 01:19:32,690
- so stubborn.
- Because...

1854
01:19:32,690 --> 01:19:35,781
- Well...
- You must follow the senior's way.

1855
01:19:37,007 --> 01:19:41,058
[The senior chef monitors every move]

1856
01:19:41,058 --> 01:19:43,794
[The stubborn junior keeps doing it
his own way...]

1857
01:19:45,330 --> 01:19:48,098
[Then he starts walking on eggshells]

1858
01:19:48,098 --> 01:19:50,993
How long have you been working here?

1859
01:19:50,993 --> 01:19:53,074
[Trying to break the awkward silence]
Here...

1860
01:19:53,074 --> 01:19:55,075
I worked here as an apprentice
when I was in culinary school.

1861
01:19:55,075 --> 01:19:56,082
Okay.

1862
01:19:56,082 --> 01:20:01,721
So I've been working here
for quite a long time.

1863
01:20:03,378 --> 01:20:07,618
[End of conversation.]

1864
01:20:08,370 --> 01:20:10,082
[They continue peeling in silence,]

1865
01:20:10,082 --> 01:20:12,530
[and peeling some more]

1866
01:20:13,730 --> 01:20:15,792
[Potato peeling complete]

1867
01:20:16,514 --> 01:20:17,714
I think I'm done.

1868
01:20:17,714 --> 01:20:19,466
- No.
- No?

1869
01:20:20,082 --> 01:20:22,658
[Time to mash the potatoes]

1870
01:20:22,658 --> 01:20:24,938
- Okay?
- Okay.

1871
01:20:25,746 --> 01:20:28,578
[Following Antonio's lead...
Grabs a handful of potatoes]

1872
01:20:28,578 --> 01:20:30,450
[Making potato mousse like a machine]

1873
01:20:31,342 --> 01:20:32,730
Kwon! How's it going?

1874
01:20:32,730 --> 01:20:35,010
- Huh?
- How's it going?

1875
01:20:35,010 --> 01:20:37,543
- It's manageable.
- You're working hard.

1876
01:20:38,866 --> 01:20:41,730
[An angelic smile]

1877
01:20:41,730 --> 01:20:44,834
You're doing great. You're fast.

1878
01:20:44,834 --> 01:20:49,410
- Thank you.
- Even we think you're fast.

1879
01:20:49,410 --> 01:20:50,482
[A slight smirk]

1880
01:20:50,482 --> 01:20:53,202
[He smiles slightly at the owner's praise]

1881
01:20:54,178 --> 01:20:57,794
[Then, Senior An approaches him again]

1882
01:20:58,434 --> 01:21:01,298
Now, finish filling the next tray.

1883
01:21:01,298 --> 01:21:04,839
[Was it from this moment?]
Now, finish filling the next tray.

1884
01:21:05,938 --> 01:21:08,834
[Senior An's close management...]

1885
01:21:09,794 --> 01:21:13,072
Never be empty-handed in the kitchen.

1886
01:21:13,072 --> 01:21:16,625
- Same when going to the dishwashing area.
- Okay.

1887
01:21:16,625 --> 01:21:19,777
[The youngest should always have full hands!]
We go to the cold room with the dirty stuff.

1888
01:21:19,777 --> 01:21:22,050
[Is he a hardship or a savior?]
On the way back, we bring the clean stuff here.

1889
01:21:22,050 --> 01:21:24,434
[How will her chemistry with Senior An be?]

1890
01:21:25,458 --> 01:21:28,367
[The third undercover chef]
I'm really looking forward to this.

1891
01:21:29,235 --> 01:21:31,391
[The warrior of the grill]
In my 24th year of cooking.

1892
01:21:31,391 --> 01:21:34,082
[Jung Ji Sun]
I'm Jung Ji Sun, a Chinese cuisine chef.

1893
01:21:35,058 --> 01:21:37,380
I have a total of 42 employees.

1894
01:21:37,380 --> 01:21:39,071
I'm currently running a restaurant

1895
01:21:39,071 --> 01:21:40,770
that blends Cantonese and Shanghai styles.

1896
01:21:40,770 --> 01:21:43,285
[What is Owner Jung Ji Sun like?]
- 42 employees? - Yes, 42.

1897
01:21:43,954 --> 01:21:45,730
Your voices are too quiet.

1898
01:21:45,730 --> 01:21:47,527
I can't hear you.

1899
01:21:48,294 --> 01:21:50,020
Aren't you going to answer?

1900
01:21:50,020 --> 01:21:52,230
[Commanding the kitchen with charisma]
You want to piss me off?

1901
01:21:52,230 --> 01:21:54,146
Are you not going to make a sound?

1902
01:21:54,146 --> 01:21:56,574
Oh, she's different. Her aura is...

1903
01:21:57,707 --> 01:22:01,208
[Korea's number one female Chinese chef]

1904
01:22:08,608 --> 01:22:12,307
[Beyond Korea to Taiwan and Hong Kong!]
Taiwan and Hong Kong are crazy for her now.

1905
01:22:12,307 --> 01:22:15,443
The first time I felt this was my path...

1906
01:22:15,443 --> 01:22:17,207
Even if school subjects didn't stick,

1907
01:22:17,207 --> 01:22:19,207
recipes always stayed in my head.

1908
01:22:19,207 --> 01:22:22,007
["My path is in the kitchen"]
I only thought about cooking.

1909
01:22:22,007 --> 01:22:24,740
It's been a while since I heard that term.

1910
01:22:24,740 --> 01:22:26,716
[The fire warrior, Chef Jung Ji Sun]
Just looking at this,

1911
01:22:26,716 --> 01:22:28,074
[What about her days as a rookie?]

1912
01:22:28,074 --> 01:22:30,266
Jung Ji Sun 24 years ago...

1913
01:22:30,266 --> 01:22:31,530
I didn't know anything.

1914
01:22:31,530 --> 01:22:33,578
I had no seniors to guide me.

1915
01:22:33,578 --> 01:22:36,026
It felt like I was starting from scratch.

1916
01:22:36,026 --> 01:22:37,930
It was very conservative.

1917
01:22:37,930 --> 01:22:39,742
Extremely conservative.

1918
01:22:39,742 --> 01:22:43,306
[Tough rookie days in a conservative field]
Back then, Chinese kitchens were even more so.

1919
01:22:43,306 --> 01:22:45,626
When a girl joins in doing something,

1920
01:22:45,626 --> 01:22:48,660
the perception changes in any kitchen.

1921
01:22:48,660 --> 01:22:50,378
They just tell you to work hard.

1922
01:22:50,378 --> 01:22:53,514
You work hard and learn skills,
but then you get married and have kids.

1923
01:22:53,514 --> 01:22:55,863
That was the mindset back then.

1924
01:22:57,018 --> 01:22:59,627
[24 years ago]
I used to think it was very unfair.

1925
01:23:00,810 --> 01:23:02,922
But then you went to study in China.

1926
01:23:02,922 --> 01:23:04,362
- Right?
- Yes.

1927
01:23:04,362 --> 01:23:05,626
[So young]

1928
01:23:05,626 --> 01:23:06,897
She was so young.

1929
01:23:06,897 --> 01:23:08,994
[Consistent eyeliner]
- She looks so fresh. - Right.

1930
01:23:08,994 --> 01:23:11,021
But even then, she had her eye makeup.

1931
01:23:11,021 --> 01:23:13,405
[What were your duties as a rookie?]
- I had some. - So young.

1932
01:23:13,405 --> 01:23:15,690
It's not like they taught me anything special

1933
01:23:15,690 --> 01:23:18,506
or gave me any specific missions.

1934
01:23:18,506 --> 01:23:20,378
[Arriving early]
I just went to work early.

1935
01:23:20,378 --> 01:23:22,330
I'd boil the large pots of broth,

1936
01:23:22,330 --> 01:23:24,020
or set up the prep station.

1937
01:23:24,020 --> 01:23:25,130
I'd prep the vegetables,

1938
01:23:25,130 --> 01:23:27,226
or finish organizing the storage.

1939
01:23:27,226 --> 01:23:29,450
[The textbook rookie]
Once I finished the basics,

1940
01:23:29,450 --> 01:23:31,514
I'd follow the seniors around

1941
01:23:31,514 --> 01:23:33,320
and help them with everything.

1942
01:23:33,320 --> 01:23:36,026
That was just the basic standard.

1943
01:23:36,026 --> 01:23:38,990
That's exactly the style I like.

1944
01:23:40,314 --> 01:23:43,290
[To the rookies of today...]
You'd be loved anywhere like that.

1945
01:23:43,290 --> 01:23:45,002
Unlike how it is these days.

1946
01:23:45,002 --> 01:23:47,080
This makes me want to say, "Back in my day."

1947
01:23:47,080 --> 01:23:49,066
The situation makes me say it.

1948
01:23:49,066 --> 01:23:51,242
I'll probably be called an old-timer again.

1949
01:23:51,242 --> 01:23:53,210
But this makes no sense.

1950
01:23:53,210 --> 01:23:54,970
During break times now...

1951
01:23:54,970 --> 01:23:57,066
I provide the ingredients for them to practice.

1952
01:23:57,066 --> 01:23:58,794
I get reports on that every day.

1953
01:23:58,794 --> 01:24:01,130
- Really?
- Practicing your knife skills is for you.

1954
01:24:01,130 --> 01:24:03,066
It's to upgrade your own skills.

1955
01:24:03,066 --> 01:24:05,418
It's not like I'm upgrading my own skills.

1956
01:24:05,418 --> 01:24:07,450
[Rookies these days]
But the kids these days...

1957
01:24:07,450 --> 01:24:10,714
It feels like they don't know what effort is.

1958
01:24:10,714 --> 01:24:13,340
[Headache]
Yes... it's very different now.

1959
01:24:14,858 --> 01:24:16,950
I'm really looking forward to this.

1960
01:24:18,301 --> 01:24:21,510
[Where will Sunny go undercover?]
- The vibe is completely different. - I know.

1961
01:24:21,510 --> 01:24:24,302
I can feel a dark energy.

1962
01:24:24,302 --> 01:24:26,186
Chengdu.

1963
01:24:26,186 --> 01:24:27,258
Sichuan.

1964
01:24:27,258 --> 01:24:28,922
[The hub of southwestern China]
Yes.

1965
01:24:28,922 --> 01:24:30,650
[The heart of Sichuan Province]

1966
01:24:30,650 --> 01:24:32,218
Sichuan is really...

1967
01:24:32,218 --> 01:24:33,712
It's really big here.

1968
01:24:33,712 --> 01:24:35,547
